{"title_page": "KFC Original Recipe", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n[[File:KFC Original Recipe chicken in bucket.jpg|thumb|KFC Original Recipe chicken]]\nThe '''KFC Original Recipe''' is a secret mix of ingredients that [[fast food restaurant]] chain [[KFC]] uses to produce [[fried chicken]].\n\n==History==\nBy the very late 1930s, [[Harland Sanders]]' [[Corbin, Kentucky]], gas station was so well known for its fried chicken, that Sanders decided to remove the gas pumps and build a restaurant and motel in its place. While perfecting his secret recipe with 11 herbs and spices, Sanders found that [[pan frying]] chicken was too slow, requiring 30 minutes per order. Deep frying the chicken required half the time, but produced dry, unevenly done chicken. In 1939 he found that using a [[Pressure frying|pressure fryer]] produced tasty, moist chicken in eight or nine minutes.<ref name=\"whitworth19700214\">{{cite news | url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1970/02/14/kentucky-fried | title=Kentucky-Fried | work=The New Yorker | date=February 14, 1970 | accessdate=April 18, 2015 | author=Whitworth, William}}</ref> By July 1940 Sanders finalized what came to be known as his Original Recipe.<ref name=july1940>{{cite news|last=Schreiner|first=Bruce|title=KFC still guards Colonel's secret|url=http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/072305/bus_19314459.shtml|accessdate=September 19, 2013|newspaper=Associated Press|date=July 23, 2005}}</ref>\n\nAfter Sanders began franchising the chicken in the 1950s as [[Kentucky Fried Chicken]], the company shipped the spices already mixed to restaurants to preserve the recipe's secrecy.{{r|whitworth19700214}} He admitted to the use of salt and pepper in the recipe, and claimed that the ingredients \"stand on everybody's shelf\".<ref name=\"AutoFE-13\">{{cite book |last=Kleber |first=John E. |author2=Thomas D. Clark |author3=Lowell H. Harrison |author4=James C. Klotter  |title=The Kentucky Encyclopedia |date=June 1992 |publisher=[[University Press of Kentucky]]|isbn=0-8131-1772-0 |page=796}}</ref><ref name=celebritychef2>{{cite book|last=Sanders|first=Harland|title=The Autobiography of the Original Celebrity Chef|year=2012|publisher=KFC|location=Louiseville|page=42|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/colcookbook/us/pdf/English_FullBook.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055011/https://s3.amazonaws.com/colcookbook/us/pdf/English_FullBook.pdf|archivedate=September 21, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSanders used [[vegetable oil]] for frying chicken. By 1993, for reasons of economy, many KFCp outlets had chosen to use a blend of palm and soybean oil. In Japan, the oil used is mainly the more expensive cottonseed and corn oil, as KFC Japan believes that this offers superior taste quality.<ref name=okawara>{{cite journal|last=Okawara|first=Takeshi|title=Universality and particularity in globalization|journal=Business Quarterly|date=Summer 1993|volume=57|issue=4|pages=128\u2013134}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSanders' Original Recipe of \"11 herbs and spices\" is one of the most famous [[trade secret]]s in the catering industry.<ref name=\"Chartrand\">{{cite news|last=Chartrand|first=Sandra|title=Patents; Many companies will forgo patents in an effort to safeguard their trade secrets|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/05/business/patents-many-companies-will-forgo-patents-effort-safeguard-their-trade-secrets.html?n=Top%2fNews%2fTechnology%2fColumns%2fPatents|newspaper=New York Times|date=February 5, 2001|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Hovey | first=C. | title=The Patent Process: A Guide to Intellectual Property for the Information Age | publisher=Wiley | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-471-44217-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aulUAAAAMAAJ | access-date=November 7, 2017 | page=243}}</ref> Franchisee [[Dave Thomas (businessman)|Dave Thomas]], better known as the founder of [[Wendy's]], argued that the secret recipe concept was successful because \"everybody wants in on a secret\" and former KFC owner [[John Y. Brown, Jr.]] called it \"a brilliant marketing ploy.\"<ref name=Darden1>{{cite book|last=Darden|first=Robert|title=Secret Recipe: Why Kfc Is Still Cooking After 50 Years|date=January 1, 2004|publisher=Tapestry Press|isbn=978-1-930819-33-7|pages=12, 57\u201358, 101, 159, 175, 211}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated58>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=R. David |title=Dave's Way: A New Approach to Old-Fashioned Success|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1j8bD6SQrAC|accessdate=April 4, 2013|date=October 1, 1992|publisher=Penguin Group (USA) Incorporated|isbn=978-0-425-13501-3|page=82}}</ref> ''The [[New York Times]]'' described the recipe as one of the company's most valuable assets.<ref name=\"Chartrand\"/> The recipe is not [[patent]]ed, because patents are published in detail and come with [[Term of patent|an expiration date]], whereas trade secrets can remain the [[intellectual property]] of their holders in perpetuity.<ref>{{cite news|title=It pays to understand law on trade secrets|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/louisville/stories/2001/02/26/editorial2.html?page=all|accessdate=February 22, 2013|newspaper=Business First|date=February 26, 2001}}</ref>\n\nKFC uses its Original Recipe as a means to differentiate its product from its competitors.<ref name=autogenerated18>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/sep/10/business/fi-kfc10 | work=Los Angeles Times | title=KFC on lookout for fowl play | date=September 10, 2008|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref> Early franchisee [[Pete Harman]] credited the chain's popularity to the recipe and the product, and John Y. Brown cites the \"incredibly tasty, almost addictive\" product as the basis of KFC's staying power.<ref name=\"AutoFE-51\">{{cite news|last=Schreiner|first=Bruce|title=Kentucky Fried Chicken marks 50th anniversary of first franchise|url=http://onlineathens.com/stories/081102/bus_20020811016.shtml|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref> On the other hand, Allen Adamson, [[managing director]] of brand consultancy [[Landor Associates|Landor]], remains unconvinced about the contribution of the secret formula aspect.<ref name=\"AutoFE-56\">{{cite news|title=Corporate Espionage; Secrets and lies|newspaper=Brand Strategy|date=October 9, 2006}}</ref> He argues: \"The story may still be part of these companies' folklore, but I'd be surprised if more than 2 percent buy the brand because of it.\"<ref name=\"AutoFE-56\" />\n\nIn reference to the original recipe, the official [[Twitter]] account of KFC follows only eleven other accounts: Six public figures (ranging from politics to sport) named Herb as well as the five members of the [[Spice Girls]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/kfc/following |title=People followed by KFC (@kfc) |website=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=August 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recipe==\nA copy of the recipe, signed by Sanders, is held safe inside a vault in KFC's Louisville headquarters, along with eleven vials containing the herbs and spices.<ref name=autogenerated21>{{cite news |title=KFC's Big Game of Chicken |author=Brady, Diane |url=http://mobile.businessweek.com/articles/2012-03-29/kfcs-big-game-of-chicken |newspaper=Businessweek |date=March 29, 2012 |accessdate=July 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115170657/http://mobile.businessweek.com/articles/2012-03-29/kfcs-big-game-of-chicken |archive-date=January 15, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |title=Colonel's Secret Recipe Gets Bodyguards |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/26618866/Colonel039s_Secret_Recipe_Gets_Bodyguards |accessdate=January 31, 2013 |newspaper=CNBC |date=September 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923032226/http://www.cnbc.com/id/26618866/Colonel039s_Secret_Recipe_Gets_Bodyguards |archivedate=September 23, 2013 }}</ref> To maintain the secrecy of the recipe, half of it is produced by Griffith Laboratories before it is given to [[McCormick & Company|McCormick]], who add the second half.<ref name=crossan>{{cite news|last=Crossan|first=Rob|title=The A to Z of fried chicken|newspaper=The Times|publisher=Times Newspapers|date=April 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, [[William Poundstone]] conducted laboratory research into the coating mix, as described in his book ''[[Big Secrets]]'', and claimed that a sample he examined contained only [[wheat flour|flour]], [[table salt|salt]], [[monosodium glutamate]] and [[black pepper]].<ref name=pound>{{cite book|last=Poundstone|first=William|title=Big Secrets|year=1983|publisher=William Morrow|isbn=0-688-04830-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bigsecretsuncens00poun/page/20 20\u201321]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/bigsecretsuncens00poun/page/20}}</ref> KFC maintains that it still adheres to Sanders' original 1940 recipe.<ref name=choi>{{cite news|last=Choi|first=Candice|title=Is Coke's 127-year-old recipe the same? Not quite|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/article/Is-Coke-s-127-year-old-recipe-the-same-Not-quite-4777106.php|date=August 26, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013|subscription=}}</ref> In [[Todd Wilbur]]'s television program ''Top Secret Recipe'', the Colonel's former secretary, Shirley Topmiller, revealed that Sanders learned from his mother that [[Salvia officinalis|sage]] and [[Summer savory|savory]] are good seasonings for chicken.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite episode |title=KFC|series=Top Secret Recipe |episodelink= |url=http://www.cmt.com/show/top_secret_recipe/episode.jhtml?episodeID=184796#moreinfo |accessdate=October 1, 2013  |serieslink= |first= |last= |network=Viacom |station=CMT |city= |date=2011 |began= |ended= |season=1 |number=101}}</ref> Also, Winston Shelton, a former friend of the Colonel, said that the secret recipe contains [[Thalassery]] black pepper.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIt is well attested that Harland Sanders asked Bill Summers of Marion-Kay Spices in [[Brownstown, Indiana]], US to recreate his secret blend of 11 herbs and spices.<ref name=\"Ozersky2\">{{cite book|last=Ozersky|first=Josh|title=Colonel Sanders and the American Dream|pages= 95\u201396 |date=April 2012|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-74285-7}}</ref> While alive, Sanders recommended the Marion-Kay seasoning to franchisees over the corporate version, as he believed the latter had been made inferior by its owners.<ref name=\"Ozersky2\" /> In 1982, after Sanders' death, KFC brought a lawsuit against Marion-Kay and the latter was barred from selling its mixture to KFC franchises.<ref name=\"Ozersky2\" /> The Marion-Kay seasoning is still sold under the name \"99-X,\" and according to Sanders biographer [[Josh Ozersky]], it is indistinguishable from the original KFC recipe.<ref name=\"Ozersky2\" />\n\nIn August 2016, the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' reported that Joe Ledington of Kentucky, a nephew by marriage of Colonel Sanders, had claimed to have found a copy of the original KFC fried chicken recipe on a handwritten piece of paper in an envelope in a scrapbook.<ref name=\"Dodrill\">{{cite web|last1=Dodrill|first1=Tara|title=KFC Secret Recipe Found? Colonel Sanders' Nephew Shares 11 Herbs And Spices Found In Family Scrapbook|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/travel/ct-kfc-recipe-revealed-20160818-story.html|date=August 19, 2016|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref> ''Tribune'' staffers conducted a cooking test of this recipe, which took several attempts to get right.<ref name=\"Dodrill\" /> They had to determine whether the \"Ts\" meant [[tablespoon]]s or [[teaspoon]]s, and soon concluded the correct interpretation was tablespoons.<ref name=\"Dodrill\" /> After some trial and error, they decided the chicken should be soaked in buttermilk and coated once in the breading mixture, then fried in oil at 350 degrees Fahrenheit in a pressure fryer until golden brown. As a pressure fryer was too big, a deep fryer was used alternatively to substitute the pressure fryer. They also claimed that with the addition of [[Monosodium glutamate|MSG]] as a flavor enhancer, they could produce fried chicken which tasted \"indistinguishable\" from fried chicken they had purchased at KFC.<ref name=\"Dodrill\" />\n\nThe recipe found by Joe Ledington reads as follows:\n\n11 Spices \u2013 Mix with 2 cups [[white flour]]\n#{{2/3}} tablespoon [[salt]]\n#{{1/2}} tablespoon [[thyme]]\n#{{1/2}} tablespoon [[basil]]\n#{{1/3}} tablespoon [[oregano]]\n#1 tablespoon [[celery salt]]\n#1 tablespoon [[black pepper]]\n#1 tablespoon [[Mustard seed|dry mustard]]\n#4 tablespoon [[paprika]]\n#2 tablespoon [[garlic salt]]\n#\n#3 tablespoon [[white pepper]]\n\nWhile Ledington expressed uncertainty that the recipe was the Original Recipe, he had a hand in mixing the Original Recipe for Colonel Sanders when he was a young boy, and recalled that white pepper was a principal ingredient.<ref name=\"Dodrill\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{KFC}}\n\n[[Category:KFC]]\n[[Category:Trade secrets]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1952]]\n[[Category:Kentucky cuisine]]\n[[Category:Fried chicken]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n[[File:KFC Original Recipe chicken in bucket.jpg|thumb|KFC Original Recipe chicken]]\nThe '''KFC Original Recipe''' is a secret mix of ingredients that [[fast food restaurant]] chain [[KFC]] uses to produce [[fried chicken]].\n\n==History==\nBy the very late 1930s, [[Harland Sanders]]' [[Corbin, Kentucky]], gas station was so well known for its fried chicken, that Sanders decided to remove the gas pumps and build a restaurant and motel in its place. While perfecting his secret recipe with 11 herbs and spices, Sanders found that [[pan frying]] chicken was too slow, requiring 30 minutes per order. Deep frying the chicken required half the time, but produced dry, unevenly done chicken. In 1939 he found that using a [[Pressure frying|pressure fryer]] produced tasty, moist chicken in eight or nine minutes.<ref name=\"whitworth19700214\">{{cite news | url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1970/02/14/kentucky-fried | title=Kentucky-Fried | work=The New Yorker | date=February 14, 1970 | accessdate=April 18, 2015 | author=Whitworth, William}}</ref> By July 1940 Sanders finalized what came to be known as his Original Recipe.<ref name=july1940>{{cite news|last=Schreiner|first=Bruce|title=KFC still guards Colonel's secret|url=http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/072305/bus_19314459.shtml|accessdate=September 19, 2013|newspaper=Associated Press|date=July 23, 2005}}</ref>\n\nAfter Sanders began franchising the chicken in the 1950s as [[Kentucky Fried Chicken]], the company shipped the spices already mixed to restaurants to preserve the recipe's secrecy.{{r|whitworth19700214}} He admitted to the use of salt and pepper in the recipe, and claimed that the ingredients \"stand on everybody's shelf\".<ref name=\"AutoFE-13\">{{cite book |last=Kleber |first=John E. |author2=Thomas D. Clark |author3=Lowell H. Harrison |author4=James C. Klotter  |title=The Kentucky Encyclopedia |date=June 1992 |publisher=[[University Press of Kentucky]]|isbn=0-8131-1772-0 |page=796}}</ref><ref name=celebritychef2>{{cite book|last=Sanders|first=Harland|title=The Autobiography of the Original Celebrity Chef|year=2012|publisher=KFC|location=Louiseville|page=42|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/colcookbook/us/pdf/English_FullBook.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921055011/https://s3.amazonaws.com/colcookbook/us/pdf/English_FullBook.pdf|archivedate=September 21, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSanders used [[vegetable oil]] for frying chicken. By 1993, for reasons of economy, many KFC outlets had chosen to use a blend of palm and soybean oil. In Japan, the oil used is mainly the more expensive cottonseed and corn oil, as KFC Japan believes that this offers superior taste quality.<ref name=okawara>{{cite journal|last=Okawara|first=Takeshi|title=Universality and particularity in globalization|journal=Business Quarterly|date=Summer 1993|volume=57|issue=4|pages=128\u2013134}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSanders' Original Recipe of \"11 herbs and spices\" is one of the most famous [[trade secret]]s in the catering industry.<ref name=\"Chartrand\">{{cite news|last=Chartrand|first=Sandra|title=Patents; Many companies will forgo patents in an effort to safeguard their trade secrets|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/02/05/business/patents-many-companies-will-forgo-patents-effort-safeguard-their-trade-secrets.html?n=Top%2fNews%2fTechnology%2fColumns%2fPatents|newspaper=New York Times|date=February 5, 2001|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Hovey | first=C. | title=The Patent Process: A Guide to Intellectual Property for the Information Age | publisher=Wiley | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-471-44217-2 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aulUAAAAMAAJ | access-date=November 7, 2017 | page=243}}</ref> Franchisee [[Dave Thomas (businessman)|Dave Thomas]], better known as the founder of [[Wendy's]], argued that the secret recipe concept was successful because \"everybody wants in on a secret\" and former KFC owner [[John Y. Brown, Jr.]] called it \"a brilliant marketing ploy.\"<ref name=Darden1>{{cite book|last=Darden|first=Robert|title=Secret Recipe: Why Kfc Is Still Cooking After 50 Years|date=January 1, 2004|publisher=Tapestry Press|isbn=978-1-930819-33-7|pages=12, 57\u201358, 101, 159, 175, 211}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated58>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=R. David |title=Dave's Way: A New Approach to Old-Fashioned Success|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y1j8bD6SQrAC|accessdate=April 4, 2013|date=October 1, 1992|publisher=Penguin Group (USA) Incorporated|isbn=978-0-425-13501-3|page=82}}</ref> ''The [[New York Times]]'' described the recipe as one of the company's most valuable assets.<ref name=\"Chartrand\"/> The recipe is not [[patent]]ed, because patents are published in detail and come with [[Term of patent|an expiration date]], whereas trade secrets can remain the [[intellectual property]] of their holders in perpetuity.<ref>{{cite news|title=It pays to understand law on trade secrets|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/louisville/stories/2001/02/26/editorial2.html?page=all|accessdate=February 22, 2013|newspaper=Business First|date=February 26, 2001}}</ref>\n\nKFC uses its Original Recipe as a means to differentiate its product from its competitors.<ref name=autogenerated18>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/sep/10/business/fi-kfc10 | work=Los Angeles Times | title=KFC on lookout for fowl play | date=September 10, 2008|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref> Early franchisee [[Pete Harman]] credited the chain's popularity to the recipe and the product, and John Y. Brown cites the \"incredibly tasty, almost addictive\" product as the basis of KFC's staying power.<ref name=\"AutoFE-51\">{{cite news|last=Schreiner|first=Bruce|title=Kentucky Fried Chicken marks 50th anniversary of first franchise|url=http://onlineathens.com/stories/081102/bus_20020811016.shtml|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref> On the other hand, Allen Adamson, [[managing director]] of brand consultancy [[Landor Associates|Landor]], remains unconvinced about the contribution of the secret formula aspect.<ref name=\"AutoFE-56\">{{cite news|title=Corporate Espionage; Secrets and lies|newspaper=Brand Strategy|date=October 9, 2006}}</ref> He argues: \"The story may still be part of these companies' folklore, but I'd be surprised if more than 2 percent buy the brand because of it.\"<ref name=\"AutoFE-56\" />\n\nIn reference to the original recipe, the official [[Twitter]] account of KFC follows only eleven other accounts: Six public figures (ranging from politics to sport) named Herb as well as the five members of the [[Spice Girls]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/kfc/following |title=People followed by KFC (@kfc) |website=[[Twitter]] |accessdate=August 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Recipe==\nA copy of the recipe, signed by Sanders, is held safe inside a vault in KFC's Louisville headquarters, along with eleven vials containing the herbs and spices.<ref name=autogenerated21>{{cite news |title=KFC's Big Game of Chicken |author=Brady, Diane |url=http://mobile.businessweek.com/articles/2012-03-29/kfcs-big-game-of-chicken |newspaper=Businessweek |date=March 29, 2012 |accessdate=July 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115170657/http://mobile.businessweek.com/articles/2012-03-29/kfcs-big-game-of-chicken |archive-date=January 15, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |title=Colonel's Secret Recipe Gets Bodyguards |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/26618866/Colonel039s_Secret_Recipe_Gets_Bodyguards |accessdate=January 31, 2013 |newspaper=CNBC |date=September 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923032226/http://www.cnbc.com/id/26618866/Colonel039s_Secret_Recipe_Gets_Bodyguards |archivedate=September 23, 2013 }}</ref> To maintain the secrecy of the recipe, half of it is produced by Griffith Laboratories before it is given to [[McCormick & Company|McCormick]], who add the second half.<ref name=crossan>{{cite news|last=Crossan|first=Rob|title=The A to Z of fried chicken|newspaper=The Times|publisher=Times Newspapers|date=April 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, [[William Poundstone]] conducted laboratory research into the coating mix, as described in his book ''[[Big Secrets]]'', and claimed that a sample he examined contained only [[wheat flour|flour]], [[table salt|salt]], [[monosodium glutamate]] and [[black pepper]].<ref name=pound>{{cite book|last=Poundstone|first=William|title=Big Secrets|year=1983|publisher=William Morrow|isbn=0-688-04830-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bigsecretsuncens00poun/page/20 20\u201321]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/bigsecretsuncens00poun/page/20}}</ref> KFC maintains that it still adheres to Sanders' original 1940 recipe.<ref name=choi>{{cite news|last=Choi|first=Candice|title=Is Coke's 127-year-old recipe the same? Not quite|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|url=http://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/article/Is-Coke-s-127-year-old-recipe-the-same-Not-quite-4777106.php|date=August 26, 2013|accessdate=October 1, 2013|subscription=}}</ref> In [[Todd Wilbur]]'s television program ''Top Secret Recipe'', the Colonel's former secretary, Shirley Topmiller, revealed that Sanders learned from his mother that [[Salvia officinalis|sage]] and [[Summer savory|savory]] are good seasonings for chicken.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite episode |title=KFC|series=Top Secret Recipe |episodelink= |url=http://www.cmt.com/show/top_secret_recipe/episode.jhtml?episodeID=184796#moreinfo |accessdate=October 1, 2013  |serieslink= |first= |last= |network=Viacom |station=CMT |city= |date=2011 |began= |ended= |season=1 |number=101}}</ref> Also, Winston Shelton, a former friend of the Colonel, said that the secret recipe contains [[Thalassery]] black pepper.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIt is well attested that Harland Sanders asked Bill Summers of Marion-Kay Spices in [[Brownstown, Indiana]], US to recreate his secret blend of 11 herbs and spices.<ref name=\"Ozersky2\">{{cite book|last=Ozersky|first=Josh|title=Colonel Sanders and the American Dream|pages= 95\u201396 |date=April 2012|publisher=University of Texas Press|isbn=978-0-292-74285-7}}</ref> While alive, Sanders recommended the Marion-Kay seasoning to franchisees over the corporate version, as he believed the latter had been made inferior by its owners.<ref name=\"Ozersky2\" /> In 1982, after Sanders' death, KFC brought a lawsuit against Marion-Kay and the latter was barred from selling its mixture to KFC franchises.<ref name=\"Ozersky2\" /> The Marion-Kay seasoning is still sold under the name \"99-X,\" and according to Sanders biographer [[Josh Ozersky]], it is indistinguishable from the original KFC recipe.<ref name=\"Ozersky2\" />\n\nIn August 2016, the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' reported that Joe Ledington of Kentucky, a nephew by marriage of Colonel Sanders, had claimed to have found a copy of the original KFC fried chicken recipe on a handwritten piece of paper in an envelope in a scrapbook.<ref name=\"Dodrill\">{{cite web|last1=Dodrill|first1=Tara|title=KFC Secret Recipe Found? Colonel Sanders' Nephew Shares 11 Herbs And Spices Found In Family Scrapbook|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/lifestyles/travel/ct-kfc-recipe-revealed-20160818-story.html|date=August 19, 2016|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref> ''Tribune'' staffers conducted a cooking test of this recipe, which took several attempts to get right.<ref name=\"Dodrill\" /> They had to determine whether the \"Ts\" meant [[tablespoon]]s or [[teaspoon]]s, and soon concluded the correct interpretation was tablespoons.<ref name=\"Dodrill\" /> After some trial and error, they decided the chicken should be soaked in buttermilk and coated once in the breading mixture, then fried in oil at 350 degrees Fahrenheit in a pressure fryer until golden brown. As a pressure fryer was too big, a deep fryer was used alternatively to substitute the pressure fryer. They also claimed that with the addition of [[Monosodium glutamate|MSG]] as a flavor enhancer, they could produce fried chicken which tasted \"indistinguishable\" from fried chicken they had purchased at KFC.<ref name=\"Dodrill\" />\n\nThe recipe found by Joe Ledington reads as follows:\n\n11 Spices \u2013 Mix with 2 cups [[white flour]]\n#{{2/3}} tablespoon [[salt]]\n#{{1/2}} tablespoon [[thyme]]\n#{{1/2}} tablespoon [[basil]]\n#{{1/3}} tablespoon [[oregano]]\n#1 tablespoon [[celery salt]]\n#1 tablespoon [[black pepper]]\n#1 tablespoon [[Mustard seed|dry mustard]]\n#4 tablespoon [[paprika]]\n#2 tablespoon [[garlic salt]]\n#\n#3 tablespoon [[white pepper]]\n\nWhile Ledington expressed uncertainty that the recipe was the Original Recipe, he had a hand in mixing the Original Recipe for Colonel Sanders when he was a young boy, and recalled that white pepper was a principal ingredient.<ref name=\"Dodrill\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{KFC}}\n\n[[Category:KFC]]\n[[Category:Trade secrets]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1952]]\n[[Category:Kentucky cuisine]]\n[[Category:Fried chicken]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c6:f48d:5d00:d121:c462:5c7f:8aff", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KFC_Original_Recipe"}
{"title_page": "John Kuan", "text_new": "{{about|the Republic of China politician|the geographic region|Guanzhong|the chancellor of the State of Qin|Guan Zhong}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name             = John Kuan<br>{{small|''Kuan Chung''}}\n|native_name      = {{lang|zh-hant|{{nobold|\u95dc\u4e2d}}}}\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image            =\n|imagesize        = \n|smallimage       = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt              = \n|caption          = \n|order1           = 11th\n|office1          = President of the Examination Yuan\n|term_start1      = 1 December 2008\n|term_end1        = 31 August 2014\n|1blankname1      = Vice\n|1namedata1       = [[Wu Jin-lin]]\n|deputy1          = \n|predecessor1     = [[Yao Chia-wen]]<br>[[Wu Jin-lin]] (acting)\n|successor1       = [[Wu Jin-lin]]\n|order2           = 11th\n|office2          = Vice President of the Examination Yuan\n|term_start2      = 1 September 1996\n|term_end2        = 30 May 2000\n|president2       = [[Hsu Shui-teh]]\n|predecessor2     = [[Mao Gao-wen]]\n|successor2       = [[Wu Rong-ming]]\n|order3           = \n|office3          = Minister of the Civil Service\n|term_start3      = 1 September 1994\n|term_end3        = 31 August 1996\n|predecessor3     = [[Chen Kuei-hua]]\n|successor3       = {{ill|Chiu Chin-yi|zh|\u90b1\u9032\u76ca}}\n|order4           = \n|office4          = Member of the [[Legislative Yuan]]\n|term_start4      = 1 February 1993\n|term_end4        = 1 September 1994\n|constituency4    = [[Taipei 1st district|Taipei 1]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1940|6|9|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Tianjin|Tientsin]], [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|China]]\n|nationality      = [[Republic of China]]\n|party            = [[Kuomintang]]\n|otherparty       = <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse           = Chang Hui-chun\n|partner          = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations        = \n|children         = Wendy Kuan\n|residence        = \n|alma_mater       = [[National Chengchi University]]<br>[[National Taiwan University]]<br>[[Tufts University]]<br>[[University of Indianapolis]]\n|occupation       = \n}}\n\n'''John Kuan''' ({{zh|c=\u95dc\u4e2d|p=Gu\u0101n Zh\u014dng}}; born 9 June 1940), also known as '''Kuan Chung''', is a [[Taiwan]]ese politician who was [[List of Presidents of the Examination Yuan|president of the Examination Yuan]] of the [[Republic of China]] from 2008 to 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exam.gov.tw/html/profile/pd-50.asp |title=President of the Examination Yuan |language=Chinese |publisher=Examination Yuan |accessdate=2009-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090317234229/http://www.exam.gov.tw/html/profile/pd-50.asp |archivedate=March 17, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKuan is of [[Manchu people|Manchu]] descent, belonging to the [[Plain White Banner]]. His surname Kuan is the sinicized form of his clan (hala) name [[G\u016bwalgiya]] ([[Manchu language|Manchu]]: {{mongolUnicode|\u1864\u1861\u1838\u1820\u182f\u1864\u1873\u1836\u1820}} {{zh|links=no|c=\u74dc\u723e\u4f73\u6c0f}}).\n\nKuan's daughter, Wendy Kuan (\u95dc\u96f2\u5a23), died in May 2011 after she fell from the kitchen window of her 27th floor apartment in [[Shanghai]]. It was rumored that she committed suicide because her husband, Zero Lin (\u6797\u54f2\u6a02), was having an affair. Kuan has avoided meeting Lin ever since his daughter's death, refusing to attend any family events where his son-in-law would be present.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yang|first1=Chiu-ying|last2=Hsu|first2=Stacy|title=FEATURE: John Kuan keeps daughter alive through grandchild|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2013/08/05/2003568974/1|accessdate=29 April 2016|work=Taipei Times|date=5 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Manchu people in Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kuan, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Indianapolis alumni]]\n[[Category:Kuomintang Members of the Legislative Yuan in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese people of Manchu descent]]\n[[Category:Republic of China politicians from Tianjin]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese Presidents of the Examination Yuan]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese Ministers of Civil Service]]\n[[Category:Manchu politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:National Chengchi University alumni]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese people from Tianjin]]\n[[Category:Taipei Members of the Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:National Taiwan University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Taiwan-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Republic of China politician|the geographic region|Guanzhong|the chancellor of the State of Qin|Guan Zhong}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = \n|name             = John Kuan<br>{{small|''Kuan Chung''}}\n|native_name      = {{lang|zh-hant|{{nobold|\u95dc\u4e2d}}}}\n|honorific-suffix = \n|image            =\n|imagesize        = \n|smallimage       = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt              = \n|caption          = \n|order1           = 11th\n|office1          = President of the Examination Yuan\n|term_start1      = 1 December 2008\n|term_end1        = 31 August 2014\n|1blankname1      = Vice\n|1namedata1       = [[Wu Jin-lin]]\n|deputy1          = \n|predecessor1     = [[Yao Chia-wen]]<br>[[Wu Jin-lin]] (acting)\n|successor1       = [[Wu Jin-lin]]\n|order2           = 11th\n|office2          = Vice President of the Examination Yuan\n|term_start2      = 1 September 1996\n|term_end2        = 30 May 2000\n|president2       = [[Hsu Shui-teh]]\n|predecessor2     = [[Mao Gao-wen]]\n|successor2       = [[Wu Rong-ming]]\n|order3           = \n|office3          = Minister of the Civil Service\n|term_start3      = 1 September 1994\n|term_end3        = 31 August 1996\n|predecessor3     = [[Chen Kuei-hua]]\n|successor3       = {{ill|Chiu Chin-yi|zh|\u90b1\u9032\u76ca}}\n|order4           = \n|office4          = Member of the [[Legislative Yuan]]\n|term_start4      = 1 February 1993\n|term_end4        = 1 September 1994\n|constituency4    = [[Taipei 1st district|Taipei 1]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1940|6|9|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Tianjin|Tientsin]], [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|China]]\n|nationality      = [[Republic of China]]\n|party            = [[Kuomintang]]\n|otherparty       = <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse           = Chang Hui-chun\n|partner          = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations        = \n|children         = Wendy Kuan\n|residence        = \n|alma_mater       = [[National Chengchi University]]<br>[[National Taiwan University]]<br>[[Tufts University]]<br>[[University of Indianapolis]]\n|occupation       = \n}}\n\n'''John Kuan''' ({{zh|c=\u95dc\u4e2d|p=Gu\u0101n Zh\u014dng}}; born 9 June 1940), also known as '''Kuan Chung''', is a [[Taiwan]]ese politician who was [[List of Presidents of the Examination Yuan|president of the Examination Yuan]] of the [[Republic of China]] from 2008 to 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exam.gov.tw/html/profile/pd-50.asp |title=President of the Examination Yuan |language=Chinese |publisher=Examination Yuan |accessdate=2009-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090317234229/http://www.exam.gov.tw/html/profile/pd-50.asp |archivedate=March 17, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKuan is of [[Manchu people|Manchu]] descent, belonging to the [[Plain White Banner]]. His surname Kuan is the sinicized form of his clan (hala) name [[G\u016bwalgiya]] ([[Manchu language|Manchu]]: {{mongolUnicode|\u1864\u1861\u1838\u1820\u182f\u1864\u1873\u1836\u1820}} Chinese: \u74dc\u723e\u4f73\u6c0f).\n\nKuan's daughter, Wendy Kuan (\u95dc\u96f2\u5a23), died in May 2011 after she fell from the kitchen window of her 27th floor apartment in [[Shanghai]]. It was rumored that she committed suicide because her husband, Zero Lin (\u6797\u54f2\u6a02), was having an affair. Kuan has avoided meeting Lin ever since his daughter's death, refusing to attend any family events where his son-in-law would be present.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Yang|first1=Chiu-ying|last2=Hsu|first2=Stacy|title=FEATURE: John Kuan keeps daughter alive through grandchild|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2013/08/05/2003568974/1|accessdate=29 April 2016|work=Taipei Times|date=5 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Manchu people in Taiwan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kuan, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Indianapolis alumni]]\n[[Category:Kuomintang Members of the Legislative Yuan in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese people of Manchu descent]]\n[[Category:Republic of China politicians from Tianjin]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese Presidents of the Examination Yuan]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese Ministers of Civil Service]]\n[[Category:Manchu politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the 2nd Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:National Chengchi University alumni]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese people from Tianjin]]\n[[Category:Taipei Members of the Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:National Taiwan University alumni]]\n{{Taiwan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: Chinese: \u2192 {{zh|links=no|c=", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Kuan"}
{"title_page": "Natalie Suleyman", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Natalie Suleyman\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Victorian Legislative Assembly|MP]]\n| image               = [[File:Natalie Suleyman MLA.jpg|frameless|]]\n| constituency_AM     = [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]]\n| assembly            = Victorian Legislative\n| term_start          = 29 November 2014\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = ''New seat''\n| majority            = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1974|6|6}}\n| birth_place         = \n| birthname           = Nazl\u0131 S\u00fcleyman\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| constituency        = \n| party               = [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]]\n| spouse              = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| profession          = \n| religion            = \n| signature           = \n| footnotes           = \n| website             = \n| committees          = Legal and Social Issues\n}}\n'''Natalie Suleyman''' (born '''Nazl\u0131 S\u00fcleyman''' on 6 June 1974) is an Australian politician, representing the [[safe seat]] electorate of [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]] in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]]. She is a member of the [[Australian Labor Party]].<ref name=\"preselect\">{{cite news|last=Livingston|first=Angus|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/west/former-brimbank-mayor-natalie-suleyman-wins-labor-party-preselection-in-st-albans/story-fngnvmj7-1226800569188|title=WEST Former Brimbank mayor Natalie Suleyman wins Labor Party preselection in St Albans|date=14 January 2014|newspaper=Herald Sun Online|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Local Politics ===\nNatalie was first elected to political office as a councillor at the [[City of Brimbank]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> She was re-elected in 2003 and 2005, and was mayor on three occasions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=107|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"farewell\">{{cite news|last=Maud|first=Paula|url=http://brimbank-leader.whereilive.com.au/news/story/suleyman-farewells-brimbank-council/|title=Suleyman farewells Brimbank council|date=28 October 2008|newspaper=Brimbank Leader|accessdate=20 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120714131409/http://brimbank-leader.whereilive.com.au/news/story/suleyman-farewells-brimbank-council/|archivedate=14 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== State Politics ===\nIn 2008, Natalie unsuccessfully contested Labor preselection for the seat of [[Electoral district of Kororoit|Kororoit]].<ref name=\"stack\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2008/s2321491.htm|title=Vic Labor MP takes party feud public|last=Caldwell|first=Alison|work=1 August 2008|publisher=ABC|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014 Natalie was preselected for the seat of [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]]. This was a new [[safe seat]], resulting from an electoral [[Redistribution (Australia)|redistribution]] creating a new seat in Melbourne's western suburbs. Natalie successfully defeated the Liberal party's candidate for the election, Moira Deeming with a 56.4% primary vote, with a [[Two-party-preferred vote|two party preferred]] result of 67.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vec.vic.gov.au/Results/State2014/StAlbansDistrict.html|title=State Election 2014: St Albans District results summary - Victorian Electoral Commission|website=www.vec.vic.gov.au|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Natalie was reelected to [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]], with a 59.7% primary vote, and [[Two-party-preferred vote|two party preferred]] result of 71.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vec.vic.gov.au/Results/State2018/StAlbansDistrict.html|title=State Election 2018: St Albans District results summary - Victorian Electoral Commission|website=www.vec.vic.gov.au|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal politics ===\nIn 2018, a plan emerged to preselect Natalie for the newly created [[Safe seat|safe]] federal seat of [[Division of Fraser (Victoria)|Fraser]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/unsinkable-jane-labor-deals-set-to-give-garrett-a-safe-spring-st-spot-20180723-p4zt1m.html|title=Unsinkable Jane: Labor deal gives Garrett a safe Spring St spot|last=Towell|first=Noel|date=2018-07-23|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> This plan faced internal backlash within the [[Australian Labor Party|Labor Party]], with [[Crikey]] reporting that the suggestion had 'sent the party into conniptions' because of Suleyman's association with the chaotic [[Brimbank Council dismissal, 2009|Brimbank City Council]]'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2018/07/26/labor-jane-garrett-deal/|title=Labor has played itself; who will make the next move?|date=2018-07-26|website=Crikey|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Reportedly, \"many in the party were aghast at the idea of parachuting Ms Suleyman (into the seat)\".<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nIn response, an plan to preselect [[Daniel Mulino]] for the seat was put forward. Mulino eventually gained preselection of the seat after being support from his [[Shop, Distributive and Allied Employees Association|associated union]] within the party.<ref name=\":02\" /> The party's manuevering to achieve this outcome caused a reshuffle in the Labor Party at both state and federal levels.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n==Misconduct findings ==\nIn June 2008, Natalie contested ALP preselection for the state seat of [[Electoral district of Kororoit|Kororoit]]. The Victorian Ombudsman found that in order to ensure her preselection, she organised a deal with former [[Electoral district of Keilor|Keilor]] state Member [[George Seitz (politician)|George Seitz]] whereby she would arrange for the funding of certain soccer-ground works, in return for his support at preselection. This gambit failed when Seitz unexpectedly withdrew his support, and the preselection was instead won by [[Marlene Kairouz]]. The Ombudsman found that Suleyman then attempted to cancel funding for the project associated with Seitz, a move that would have cost the council more than $300,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/west/former-brimbank-mayor-natalie-suleyman-wins-labor-party-preselection-in-st-albans/news-story/1b40819a14ab04b70ce25800cf24a33a|title=Suleyman preselected in St Albans|date=2014-01-13|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nThese events led to Seitz invoking [[Parliamentary privilege]] to criticise Suleyman on the floor of the Victorian Parliament. Seitz's comments, widely reported, included an accusation that Suleyman was the 'Robert Mugabe of Brimbank', and had improperly interfered with local sporting clubs associated with Seitz; in response to her lost preselection.<ref name=\"stack\" />\n\nResultant reporting prompted an investigation by the [[Ombudsmen in Australia|Victorian Ombudsman]] into alleged misconduct at [[City of Brimbank|Brimbank Council]].<ref name=\"rats\">{{cite news|last=Crook|first=Andrew|title=Brimbank Council's rats in the ranks saga|url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2009/05/11/brimbank-report-could-prove-fatal-for-seitz/|accessdate=20 January 2014|date=11 May 2009}}</ref> Regarding the allegations made by [[George Seitz (politician)|Seitz]] in parliament, the Ombudsman found that Natalie had indeed directed the council CEO to withdraw funding from development works at the Keilor Lodge Reserve, which 'had the CEO complied with the direction, (would have put the council) in breach of contract and at significant financial risk'. Natalie's explanation to the ombudsman that she was not involved in the issuing of the direction was found by the ombudsman to have been 'an attempt to mislead',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=57|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> with a finding made that 'the direction was issued in retalation for Suleyman's pre-selection loss'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=65|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> This led to a further finding that Suleyman had breached s76B(3) of the Local Government Act, having made improper use of her position. The ombudsman recommended that the breach be investigated by the Victorian department responsible for local government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=66|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe other significant finding within the report, was that Suleyman had made an improper and informal demand that $680,000 be allocated to a project at [[Cairnlea, Victoria|Cairnlea Park]], at a facility in which clubs to which Suleyman's family were linked.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=77|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The ombudsman found that after the budget had been finalised at a council workshop, Suleyman had approached council staff and threatened to prevent the budget from being adopted unless her projects were funded. The council executive were found to have altered in scope several council items to ensure the demand could be accommodated. The ombudsman found that: <blockquote>\"The alleged actions of Cr Suleyman appeared to breach the councillor oath of office, which requires that councillors act in the best interests of the community. It is also clearly a misuse of Cr Suleyman\u2019s position as a councillor. In addition, I was concerned that the Brimbank officers acceded to Cr Suleyman\u2019s \u2018demand\u2019 without referring the matter to the whole council.\"<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>Other findings regarding Suleyman's conduct included:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=May 2009|website=Victorian Parliament|publisher=Victorian government printer|page=105|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.org/details/vparl200610no188a|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* A misuse of council processes to further harass Seitz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001  Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Findings of abuse and aggression toward Council officers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* An improper insistence that council spend $572 on library membership cards bearing her signature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Inappropriate disposal of confidential council documents.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Enabling the rent-free access of her father to a council building with an ordinary annual lease value of over $15,000 (since 1999); and improperly accessing council files relating to that building. In 2006, following public scrutiny of this arrangement in a local newspaper, the property's $1,700 per year [[Peppercorn (legal)|peppercorn]] lease (drawn up by the council in 2002) was then complied with.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=114|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The ombudsman also found that Natalie had been involved in procuring $11,000 worth of building works for the benefit of her father at the property, writing 'It is apparent that Mr Suleyman received favourable treatment due to his daughter's influence'. Natalie denied these findings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=117|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n* An Engagement of 'subterfuge' against the Ombudsman, by having manipulated another councillor to sign a complaint letter to the Ombudsman in their name, when the letter had in fact been written by Natalie and another councillor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=109|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Local Government Inspectorate took no action against Natalie in the wake of the report.<ref name=\"probe\">{{cite news|last=Rood|first=David|title=Brimbank probe decides on no action|url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/brimbank-probe-decides-on-no-action-20091213-kqij.html|accessdate=20 January 2014|newspaper=The Age|date=14 December 2009}}</ref> In a letter seen by the local newspaper [[Brimbank & North West Star Weekly|Brimbank Weekly]] the inspectorate claimed to have found 'insufficient evidence to support a prosecution'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/west/former-brimbank-mayor-natalie-suleyman-wins-labor-party-preselection-in-st-albans/news-story/1b40819a14ab04b70ce25800cf24a33a|title=Suleyman preselected in St Albans|date=2014-01-13|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nThe Ombudsman's report led to the passage of new laws banning councillors from working as staffers to members of Parliament. It also played a role in the eventual sacking of Brimbank Council in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/brimbank-council-to-be-suspended-by-state-government-after-damning-report-into-the-western-suburbs-municipality/news-story/afd369d28983458279c515ed3d4701ec|title=Brimbank Council sacked|date=2009-09-15|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Awards & Honours ==\nNatalie has received the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]],<ref name=\"about page\">url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190312025116/http://www.nataliesuleyman.com.au/details/about-natalie/</ref> and an award from the Australian Society of Polish Jews and their descendants named after [[Henryk S\u0142awik]].<ref name=\"HAYNT\">url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128225326/https://www.polishjews.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2019_spring.pdf</ref>\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://vicvote.review/assembly/members/Natalie%20Suleyman.html Parliamentary voting record]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{s-new|seat}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]] | years=2014&ndash;present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{VicCurrentMLAs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suleyman, Nazli}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Turkish Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Natalie Suleyman\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Victorian Legislative Assembly|MP]]\n| image               = [[File:Natalie Suleyman MLA.jpg|frameless|]]\n| constituency_AM     = [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]]\n| assembly            = Victorian Legislative\n| term_start          = 29 November 2014\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = ''New seat''\n| majority            = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1974|6|6}}\n| birth_place         = \n| birthname           = Nazl\u0131 S\u00fcleyman\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| constituency        = \n| party               = [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]]\n| spouse              = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| profession          = \n| religion            = \n| signature           = \n| footnotes           = \n| website             = \n| committees          = Legal and Social Issues\n}}\n'''Natalie Suleyman''' (born '''Nazl\u0131 S\u00fcleyman''' on 6 June 1974) is an Australian politician, representing the electorate of [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]] in the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]]. She is a member of the [[Australian Labor Party]].<ref name=\"preselect\">{{cite news|last=Livingston|first=Angus|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/west/former-brimbank-mayor-natalie-suleyman-wins-labor-party-preselection-in-st-albans/story-fngnvmj7-1226800569188|title=WEST Former Brimbank mayor Natalie Suleyman wins Labor Party preselection in St Albans|date=14 January 2014|newspaper=Herald Sun Online|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n=== Local Politics ===\nNatalie was first elected to political office as a councillor at the [[City of Brimbank]] in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=24|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> She was re-elected in 2003 and 2005, and was mayor on three occasions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=107|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"farewell\">{{cite news|last=Maud|first=Paula|url=http://brimbank-leader.whereilive.com.au/news/story/suleyman-farewells-brimbank-council/|title=Suleyman farewells Brimbank council|date=28 October 2008|newspaper=Brimbank Leader|accessdate=20 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120714131409/http://brimbank-leader.whereilive.com.au/news/story/suleyman-farewells-brimbank-council/|archivedate=14 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== State Politics ===\nIn 2008, Natalie unsuccessfully contested Labor preselection for the seat of [[Electoral district of Kororoit|Kororoit]].<ref name=\"stack\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2008/s2321491.htm|title=Vic Labor MP takes party feud public|last=Caldwell|first=Alison|work=1 August 2008|publisher=ABC|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014 Natalie was preselected for the seat of [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]]. This was a new [[safe seat]], resulting from an electoral [[Redistribution (Australia)|redistribution]] creating a new seat in Melbourne's western suburbs. Natalie successfully defeated the Liberal party's candidate for the election, Moira Deeming with a 56.4% primary vote, with a [[Two-party-preferred vote|two party preferred]] result of 67.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vec.vic.gov.au/Results/State2014/StAlbansDistrict.html|title=State Election 2014: St Albans District results summary - Victorian Electoral Commission|website=www.vec.vic.gov.au|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 Natalie was reelected to [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]], with a 59.7% primary vote, and [[Two-party-preferred vote|two party preferred]] result of 71.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vec.vic.gov.au/Results/State2018/StAlbansDistrict.html|title=State Election 2018: St Albans District results summary - Victorian Electoral Commission|website=www.vec.vic.gov.au|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal politics ===\nIn 2018, a plan emerged to preselect Natalie for the newly created [[Safe seat|safe]] federal seat of [[Division of Fraser (Victoria)|Fraser]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/victoria/unsinkable-jane-labor-deals-set-to-give-garrett-a-safe-spring-st-spot-20180723-p4zt1m.html|title=Unsinkable Jane: Labor deal gives Garrett a safe Spring St spot|last=Towell|first=Noel|date=2018-07-23|website=The Age|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> This plan faced internal backlash within the [[Australian Labor Party|Labor Party]], with [[Crikey]] reporting that the suggestion had 'sent the party into conniptions' because of Suleyman's association with the chaotic [[Brimbank Council dismissal, 2009|Brimbank City Council]]'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2018/07/26/labor-jane-garrett-deal/|title=Labor has played itself; who will make the next move?|date=2018-07-26|website=Crikey|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Reportedly, \"many in the party were aghast at the idea of parachuting Ms Suleyman (into the seat)\".<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nIn response, an plan to preselect [[Daniel Mulino]] for the seat was put forward. Mulino eventually gained preselection of the seat after being support from his [[Shop, Distributive and Allied Employees Association|associated union]] within the party.<ref name=\":02\" /> The party's manuevering to achieve this outcome caused a reshuffle in the Labor Party at both state and federal levels.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\n==Misconduct findings ==\nIn June 2008, Natalie contested ALP preselection for the state seat of [[Electoral district of Kororoit|Kororoit]]. The Victorian Ombudsman found that in order to ensure her preselection, she organised a deal with former [[Electoral district of Keilor|Keilor]] state Member [[George Seitz (politician)|George Seitz]] whereby she would arrange for the funding of certain soccer-ground works, in return for his support at preselection. This gambit failed when Seitz unexpectedly withdrew his support, and the preselection was instead won by [[Marlene Kairouz]]. The Ombudsman found that Suleyman then attempted to cancel funding for the project associated with Seitz, a move that would have cost the council more than $300,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/west/former-brimbank-mayor-natalie-suleyman-wins-labor-party-preselection-in-st-albans/news-story/1b40819a14ab04b70ce25800cf24a33a|title=Suleyman preselected in St Albans|date=2014-01-13|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nThese events led to Seitz invoking [[Parliamentary privilege]] to criticise Suleyman on the floor of the Victorian Parliament. Seitz's comments, widely reported, included an accusation that Suleyman was the 'Robert Mugabe of Brimbank', and had improperly interfered with local sporting clubs associated with Seitz; in response to her lost preselection.<ref name=\"stack\" />\n\nResultant reporting prompted an investigation by the [[Ombudsmen in Australia|Victorian Ombudsman]] into alleged misconduct at [[City of Brimbank|Brimbank Council]].<ref name=\"rats\">{{cite news|last=Crook|first=Andrew|title=Brimbank Council's rats in the ranks saga|url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2009/05/11/brimbank-report-could-prove-fatal-for-seitz/|accessdate=20 January 2014|date=11 May 2009}}</ref> Regarding the allegations made by [[George Seitz (politician)|Seitz]] in parliament, the Ombudsman found that Natalie had indeed directed the council CEO to withdraw funding from development works at the Keilor Lodge Reserve, which 'had the CEO complied with the direction, (would have put the council) in breach of contract and at significant financial risk'. Natalie's explanation to the ombudsman that she was not involved in the issuing of the direction was found by the ombudsman to have been 'an attempt to mislead',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=57|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> with a finding made that 'the direction was issued in retalation for Suleyman's pre-selection loss'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=65|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> This led to a further finding that Suleyman had breached s76B(3) of the Local Government Act, having made improper use of her position. The ombudsman recommended that the breach be investigated by the Victorian department responsible for local government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=66|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe other significant finding within the report, was that Suleyman had made an improper and informal demand that $680,000 be allocated to a project at [[Cairnlea, Victoria|Cairnlea Park]], at a facility in which clubs to which Suleyman's family were linked.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=77|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The ombudsman found that after the budget had been finalised at a council workshop, Suleyman had approached council staff and threatened to prevent the budget from being adopted unless her projects were funded. The council executive were found to have altered in scope several council items to ensure the demand could be accommodated. The ombudsman found that: <blockquote>\"The alleged actions of Cr Suleyman appeared to breach the councillor oath of office, which requires that councillors act in the best interests of the community. It is also clearly a misuse of Cr Suleyman\u2019s position as a councillor. In addition, I was concerned that the Brimbank officers acceded to Cr Suleyman\u2019s \u2018demand\u2019 without referring the matter to the whole council.\"<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>Other findings regarding Suleyman's conduct included:<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=May 2009|website=Victorian Parliament|publisher=Victorian government printer|page=105|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.org/details/vparl200610no188a|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n* A misuse of council processes to further harass Seitz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001  Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Findings of abuse and aggression toward Council officers.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* An improper insistence that council spend $572 on library membership cards bearing her signature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Inappropriate disposal of confidential council documents.<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Enabling the rent-free access of her father to a council building with an ordinary annual lease value of over $15,000 (since 1999); and improperly accessing council files relating to that building. In 2006, following public scrutiny of this arrangement in a local newspaper, the property's $1,700 per year [[Peppercorn (legal)|peppercorn]] lease (drawn up by the council in 2002) was then complied with.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=114|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref> The ombudsman also found that Natalie had been involved in procuring $11,000 worth of building works for the benefit of her father at the property, writing 'It is apparent that Mr Suleyman received favourable treatment due to his daughter's influence'. Natalie denied these findings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=117|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n* An Engagement of 'subterfuge' against the Ombudsman, by having manipulated another councillor to sign a complaint letter to the Ombudsman in their name, when the letter had in fact been written by Natalie and another councillor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|title=Whistleblowers Protection Act 2001 Investigation into the alleged improper conduct of councillors at Brimbank City Council|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=109|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200418060120/https://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/papers/govpub/VPARL2006-10No188A.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe Local Government Inspectorate took no action against Natalie in the wake of the report.<ref name=\"probe\">{{cite news|last=Rood|first=David|title=Brimbank probe decides on no action|url=http://www.theage.com.au/national/brimbank-probe-decides-on-no-action-20091213-kqij.html|accessdate=20 January 2014|newspaper=The Age|date=14 December 2009}}</ref> In a letter seen by the local newspaper [[Brimbank & North West Star Weekly|Brimbank Weekly]] the inspectorate claimed to have found 'insufficient evidence to support a prosecution'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/west/former-brimbank-mayor-natalie-suleyman-wins-labor-party-preselection-in-st-albans/news-story/1b40819a14ab04b70ce25800cf24a33a|title=Suleyman preselected in St Albans|date=2014-01-13|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nThe Ombudsman's report led to the passage of new laws banning councillors from working as staffers to members of Parliament. It also played a role in the eventual sacking of Brimbank Council in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/brimbank-council-to-be-suspended-by-state-government-after-damning-report-into-the-western-suburbs-municipality/news-story/afd369d28983458279c515ed3d4701ec|title=Brimbank Council sacked|date=2009-09-15|website=www.heraldsun.com.au|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Awards & Honours ==\nNatalie has received the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]],<ref name=\"about page\">url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190312025116/http://www.nataliesuleyman.com.au/details/about-natalie/</ref> and an award from the Australian Society of Polish Jews and their descendants named after [[Henryk S\u0142awik]].<ref name=\"HAYNT\">url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128225326/https://www.polishjews.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2019_spring.pdf</ref>\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [http://vicvote.review/assembly/members/Natalie%20Suleyman.html Parliamentary voting record]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{s-new|seat}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member for [[Electoral district of St Albans|St Albans]] | years=2014&ndash;present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{VicCurrentMLAs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suleyman, Nazli}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Turkish Cypriot descent]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n", "name_user": "Wikiparlproject", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natalie_Suleyman"}
{"title_page": "1997 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World", "text_new": "{{American Championship Car race report infobox\n|Country       = USA\n|Race          = Walt Disney World\n|Image         = Walt_Disney_World_Speedway_diagram.svg\n|Date          = January 25\n|Year          = 1997\n|1996-1997     = yes\n|Official name = [[Delphi Indy 200|Indy 200 at Walt Disney World]]\n|Round_No      = 3rd\n|Series        = Indy Racing League\n|Location      = [[Walt Disney World Speedway]]\n|Course        = Permanent racing facility\n|Course_mi     = 1.000\n|Course_km     = 1.609\n|Distance_laps = 149\n|Distance_mi   = 149.000\n|Distance_km   = 239.792\n|Scheduled_laps = 200\n|Scheduled_mi   = 200.000\n|Scheduled_km   = 321.869\n|Weather       = Mixture of dry weather and rain; temperatures reaching up to {{convert|75.2|F|C}} along with wind speeds reaching up to {{convert|20|mph|km/h}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almanac.com/weather/history/zipcode/32821/1997-01-25 |title=''1997 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World'' weather information |publisher=Old Farmers' Almanac|accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>\n|Pole_Driver   = [[Tony Stewart]]\n|Pole_Team     = [[Team Menard]]\n|Pole_Time     = 21.685\n|Pole_Country  = USA\n|Fast_Driver   = [[Tony Stewart]]\n|Fast_Team     = [[Team Menard]]\n|Fast_Time     = 22.579\n|Fast_Lap      = 5\n|Fast_Country  = USA\n|First_Driver  = [[Eddie Cheever]]\n|First_Team    = [[Cheever Racing|Team Cheever]]\n|First_Country = USA\n|Second_Driver = [[Mike Groff]]\n|Second_Team   = [[Byrd-Cunningham Racing]]\n|Second_Country = USA\n|Third_Driver  = [[Scott Goodyear]]\n|Third_Team    = [[Treadway Racing]]\n|Third_Country = USA\n}}\n\nThe '''1997 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World''' was the third round of the [[1996\u20131997 in IRL|1996\u20131997 Indy Racing League]]. The race was held on January 25, 1997, at the {{convert|1.000|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Walt Disney World Speedway]] in [[Bay Lake, Florida]], being the first IRL race of the calendar year 1997. It was the first race with the new chassis from [[Dallara]] and [[Panoz|G-Force]], as well as for the 4000 cc naturally aspirated engines supplied by [[Oldsmobile]] and [[Infiniti]], and it marked the first time that a major open-wheel series contested a race with brand-new cars and engines. The race was won by [[Eddie Cheever]] after being called off on lap 149 of the scheduled 200 due to heavy rain.<ref name=\"Lucky Victory Is Sweet To Star-Crossed Cheever\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/26/sports/lucky-victory-is-sweet-to-star-crossed-cheever.html?scp=4&sq=1997%20Indy%20200&st=cse|title=Lucky Victory Is Sweet To Star-Crossed Cheever|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2009-07-02 | first=Joseph | last=Siano | date=January 26, 1997}}</ref>\n\n==Report==\n===Pre-Race===\nThe Indy Racing League was faced with a four-month break between the second and third round, due to the nature of the 1996-97 calendar. This, combined with the addition of rounds at Texas and Pikes Peak that nullified a summer break, the criticism about the Indianapolis 500 overshadowing the co-championship of [[Buzz Calkins]] and [[Scott Sharp]],<ref name=\"CoChampions\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961106105328/http://icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=14|title=News from the IRL - IRL starts new season|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=June 27, 1996}}</ref> and the majority of motorsport series and potential sponsors following a calendar-based approach, led the teams to complain about the split season.<ref name=\"IRL9697\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theautochannel.com/sports/openwheel/1022irl.html|title=IRL season will go with the normal calendar year|publisher=The Auto Channel|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 22, 1996}}</ref> On October 9, it was confirmed that the season would go beyond the Indianapolis 500, ending at the [[1997 Las Vegas 500K]], and that the series would switch to a calendar-based format for the 1998 season.<ref name=\"Calendar\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-seasons-to-change-to-claendar-years/|title=IRL: Seasons to change to calendar years|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 9, 1996}}</ref> Thus, the season schedule went from five to nine races. Following a successful test by [[Team Menard]] on September 25, with [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]] subbing for the injured [[Tony Stewart]] and [[Mark Dismore]]<ref name=\"CharlotteTest\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theautochannel.com/news/date/19961021/news02300.html|title=Looks Like There May Be an IRL Race at Charlotte in 1997|publisher=The Auto Channel|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 21, 1996}}</ref> with a fastest lap of 207.61&nbsp;mph, the IRL confirmed on December 17 a tenth round at [[Charlotte Motor Speedway]], to be held on July 26.<ref name=\"SunRace\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216163404/http://brickyard.com:80/irl/1996/96pr-061.htm|title=IRL heads to the heartland of Charlotte|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 17, 1996}}</ref>\n\nThe future of [[Tony Stewart]], who had his sights on a [[NASCAR]] ride and missed his [[Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series|Winston Cup]] debut at Atlanta as a result of the injuries sustained at Las Vegas,<ref name=\"StewartStory\">{{cite news |url=https://www.racing-reference.info/showblog?id=2829|title=Tony Stewart's Planned Cup Debut|publisher=racing-reference.info|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 17, 2016}}</ref> was one of the big stories of the winter gap. Being only contracted with [[Team Menard]] through the original end of the season at Indianapolis,<ref name=\"MenardIndy\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090239/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=35|title=Stewart to run NASCAR, not IRL|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=September 20, 1996}}</ref> it was announced on September 17 that he would race full-time in the [[1997 NASCAR Winston Cup Series]] with his [[NASCAR Xfinity Series|Busch Series]] owner, [[Ranier Racing with MDM|Harry Ranier]].<ref name=\"StewartNASCAR\">{{cite news|url=https://articles.dailypress.com/1996-09-19/sports/9609190007_1_winston-cup-race-felix-sabates-robby-gordon|title=Stewart likely staying put|publisher=Daily Press|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=September 19, 1996}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, the deal fell through a month later, as a clause that estipulated that enough sponsorship for the full season had to be found by mid-October was not fulfilled.<ref name=\"StewartStory\"/><ref name=\"KOOL\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090204/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=39|title=IndyCar News - Who's Kool?|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 3, 1996}}</ref> During that month, it was reported that [[Andretti Autosport|Team Green]] tried to lure Stewart to its [[Kool (cigarette)|KOOL]]-backed CART operation for 1997,<ref name=\"KOOL\"/> and that [[General Motors]] wanted to get Stewart back from [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] by stablishing an IRL full-time operation centered around him with [[Hendrick Motorsports]], combined with a partial Busch Series schedule. However, Hendrick denied this information,<ref name=\"StewartStory\"/> and both negotiations were reported to have collapsed weeks later.<ref name=\"GreenNot\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090059/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=44|title=Team Green Looking Abroad|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 30, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"HendrickNot\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090026/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=46|title=Team Green still up in the air|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 15, 1996}}</ref>\n\nFrom September 30 to October 4, USAC organized a five-day test exclusively aimed at driver's tests, conducted with the [[PDM Racing]] 'mule' car. A total of 7 drivers passed their test, although only three of them would take part in an IRL race: [[Robbie Groff]], who had two IndyCar races under his belt, [[United States Auto Club#USAC Silver Crown Series|USAC Silver Crown]]  champion [[Jack Hewitt]] and [[ARCA Racing Series|ARCA]] champion and [[World of Outlaws]] race-winner [[Andy Hillenburg]]. The other four were [[1992 Atlantic Championship|Formula Atlantic]] champion [[Chris Smith (racing driver)|Chris Smith]], supermodified driver [[Mike Muldoon (racing driver)|Mike Muldoon]] and Silver Crown veterans [[Cary Faas]] and [[Jim Keeker]].<ref name=\"USACDrivers\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-phoenix-driver-testing-96-10-04/|title=Hewitt, Robbie Groff, 5 others pass IRL driver's tests|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 4, 1996}}</ref> [[IMSA GT Championship|IMSA]] regular [[Tom Hessert]] also passed his test on a conditional basis, and [[Butch Brickell]], recovered from the injuries sustained at [[Walt Disney World Speedway]], only passed two phases.<ref name=\"44Drivers\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216163708/http://brickyard.com:80/irl/1996/96pr-047.htm|title=USAC driver's tests made 44 drivers eligible for IRL competition|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 6, 1996}}</ref> On October 6, [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]] got the overall win at the 3 Hours of Daytona, the last round of the IMSA GT season, with a handful of other IRL regulars in competition.\n\nDespite reports that the introduction of the new chassis and engine formula could be postponed, testing went ahead as scheduled.<ref name=\"Delay\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theautochannel.com/sports/openwheel/1022chassis.html|title=IRL chassis debut could be postponed|publisher=The Auto Channel|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 23, 1996}}</ref> With the [[Riley & Scott]] chassis being projected to debut at the Texas 500 after having been commissioned by [[Kelley Racing|Kelley Automotive Group]],<ref name=\"RileyScott\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-riley-scott-takes-first-irl-chassis-order/|title=Riley & Scott takes first IRL chassis order, plan competition debut in Longhorn 500|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 23, 1996}}</ref> whose initial plans were to resell the cars at a later date,<ref name=\"KelleySales\">{{cite news |url=http://www.news-sentinel.com/sports/top-sports/2015/05/21/hitting-the-bricksbrq-and-a-with-tom-kelley-brbrkelley-recalls-highs-and-lows-of-owning-a-racing-team/|title=Kelley recalls highs and lows of owning a racing team|publisher=[[Knoxville News Sentinel]]|accessdate=February 7, 2019|date=May 21, 2015}}</ref> the [[Panoz|G-Force]] chassis and the [[Oldsmobile]] engine made their debut at [[ISM Raceway|Phoenix]] on November 13\u201315 with [[Treadway Racing]] and [[Arie Luyendyk]] running 175 laps, and a best lap in the 162&nbsp;mph range.<ref name=\"GForceICR\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090012/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=47|title=Luyendyk tests G-Force/Aurora IRL car|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 21, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"GForceMotorsport\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-phoenix-aurora-g-force-test/|title=Aurora V8 completes first track test|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 15, 1996}}</ref> [[Dallara]] did so on November 25\u201326 at [[Walt Disney World Speedway|Walt Disney World]] with [[Team Scandia]] and [[Eliseo Salazar]], who did 203 laps and a best lap of 157&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"DallaraICR\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625085951/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=48|title=Dallara runs at Disney World|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 29, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"DallaraBrickyard\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216163610/http://brickyard.com:80/irl/1996/96pr-051.htm|title=Salazar, Team Scandia complete first Dallara test|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 26, 1996}}</ref> However, by the time of the open test at Walt Disney World on December 10\u201313, [[Oldsmobile]]'s engine production had been scarce, and [[Infiniti]] was not ready to supply theirs.<ref name=\"InfinitiDelay\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625085929/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=49|title=Weekly News Update: Infiniti Delayed|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 4, 1996}}</ref> [[Arie Luyendyk]], [[Tony Stewart]] and [[Scott Sharp]] were the only drivers to take part, with Luyendyk setting a fastest lap of 166.898&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"TestWDW1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-testing-96-12-13/|title=Luyendyk sets top testing speed at 166.898&nbsp;mph at Walt Disney World|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 13, 1996}}</ref> Those tests were the first overseen by the new IRL executive director and vice president Leo Mehl, the former general manager for [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]].<ref name=\"Mehl\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-new-director-ims-staff-changes/|title=Tony George Announces New IRL Head and Additions To IMS Corporate Team |publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 2, 1996}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, the litigation between the IRL and CART regarding the use of the \"IndyCar\" trademark, and the one filled by [[A. J. Foyt]] for anti-competitive practices, ended in an out-of-court settlement \"without any acknowledgment of fault or liability by any party\".  CART agreed to end its licensing agreement with the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]] and cease use of the term \"IndyCar\" for their series, but its use by the IRL would be prohibited until 2003, as part of the settlement.<ref name=\"litigation\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-champcar-cart-cart-ims-litigation-ended/|title=CART and IMS Litigation Ended|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 17, 1996}}</ref> That same day, Joie Chitwood Jr. confirmed the formation of a new team, [[Chitwood Motorsports]], with veteran [[Danny Ongais]] as a driver,<ref name=\"Test 17-12\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-test-96-12-17/|title=Salazar Continues at Walt Disney World; Galles, Jones on Track at Phoenix|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 17, 1996}}</ref> and [[Treadway Racing]] followed suit by announcing [[Scott Goodyear]] as a driver for their second car, the two-time Indy 500 runner-up having only run partially in IndyCar for the last two years.<ref name=\"Goodyear\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-phoenix-test-96-12-18/|title=Salazar hits 164.285 miles per hour at Walt Disney World Speedway|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 18, 1996}}</ref> At the resuming of open tests at [[Walt Disney World Speedway]] from December 16\u201322, Goodyear led the proceedings with a 168.145&nbsp;mph lap. Stewart, Salazar, [[Eddie Cheever]], [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]] and [[Buzz Calkins]] also tested, while [[Galles Racing]] and [[Davy Jones (racing driver)|Davy Jones]] elected to do so at [[ISM Raceway|Phoenix International Raceway]].<ref name=\"TestOverall\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625085834/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=53|title=Goodyear Tops IRL Disney World Testing|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 24, 1996}}</ref>\n\nTesting at Orlando continued throughout the first weeks of January, with 10 drivers taking part, among them [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]] with [[Team Scandia]]. [[Tony Stewart]] put a best lap just south of the 170&nbsp;mph mark (169.795&nbsp;mph),<ref name=\"JanuaryTests\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625085823/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=54|title=Salazar Hurt at Disney World|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 17, 1997}}</ref> and [[Mike Groff]] debuted the [[Infiniti]] engine, getting close to 160&nbsp;mph in his best effort.<ref name=\"Groffiniti\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-test-97-01-15/|title=Groff, Byrd/Cunningham finish Nissan test; Hemelgarn, Lazier arrive at Walt Disney World Speedway|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 15, 1997}}</ref> They were joined by [[Buddy Lazier]], who got to do some system-check laps with the [[Infiniti]],<ref name=\"LazierInf\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216151020/http://brickyard.com:80/irl/97pr-009.htm|title=NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series haulers arrive; Lazier tests|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 16, 1997}}</ref> and Dr. [[Jack Miller (racing driver)|Jack Miller]], a veteran [[Indy Lights]] competitor who passed his rookie test in the [[PDM Racing]] 'mule' car. Miller, known as 'The Racing Dentist' for his full-time job, had arranged a deal with the [[Arizona Motorsports]] rental crew to race in 1997.<ref name=\"Test11\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-test-97-1-11/|title=Salazar hospitalized after testing accident|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 11, 1997}}</ref> On January 11, [[Eliseo Salazar]] lost control of his car after having an engine failure and crashed in Turn 1, suffering a compression fracture in his lower back.<ref name=\"Test11\"/> Salazar, injured at Orlando for the second year in a row, was ruled out of action \"at least until the beginning of May\".<ref name=\"Groffiniti\"/> On January 16, both [[Jeret Schroeder]], a [[U.S. F2000]] champion and top-5 contender in the [[Atlantic Championship]], and [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]] were confirmed to drive for [[McCormack Motorsports]] and Blueprint Racing, respectively.<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970617070115fw_/http://www.racelink.com/rl_news/archive/01_97/drn_wk3.html|title=RaceLink Daily Racing News - January 1997, Week 3|publisher=RaceLink.com|accessdate=February 7, 2019|date=January 16, 1997}}</ref><ref name=\"Test21\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-testing-97-01-21/|title=Lazier turns fastest Nissan-powered lap at 162.162; Schroeder passes rookie test, readies for Indy 200 weekend|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 21, 1997}}</ref>\n\n===Practice and qualifying===\n\nFurther testing was conducted on the week of the race with 11 drivers, among them [[Roberto Guerrero]] and [[Marco Greco]], designated by [[Team Scandia]] as Salazar's replacement.<ref name=\"Test20\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-testing-97-01-20/|title=Lazier tests Hemelgarn Dallara/Infiniti; teams start arriving for Indy 200 at Walt Disney World|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 20, 1997}}</ref> [[Tony Stewart]] logged the fastest lap at 165.975&nbsp;mph, with [[Buddy Lazier]] in close pursuit in his [[Infiniti]]-powered car.<ref name=\"Test22\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-testing-97-01-22/|title=Stewart tops among nine drivers on final winter testing day|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 22, 1997}}</ref> The entry list was unveiled on January 21 with 22 car/driver combinations, but [[Mark Dismore]], [[Robbie Buhl]] and [[Sam Schmidt]] were later withdrawn due to the widespread parts shortage that left them out of any winter testing.<ref name=\"Notes\"/> [[Davey Hamilton]] also had to skip winter testing for the same reason, but he remained entered nonetheless. The drivers already confirmed were joined by [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]] driving for a new team, [[Chastain Motorsports]].<ref name=\"Entry\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216154516/http://brickyard.com:80/wdw/97entry.htm|title=1997 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World, Tentative Entry List|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 21, 1997}}</ref> On Thursday, [[Stan Wattles]] announced his plans to become an driver-owner under the Metro Racing System banner he had driven with in Formula Atlantics. The deadline was set for a late 1997 start at the earliest, in anticipation of a full-season effort in 1998.\n\nThursday practice was dominated by [[Tony Stewart]], who led with a 167.715&nbsp;mph lap in the morning session<ref name=\"ThursMorning\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-thursday-am-practice/|title=WDW: Thursday AM Practice|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 23, 1997}}</ref> and a 165.738&nbsp;mph lap in the afternoon, with [[Buzz Calkins]] and [[Buddy Lazier]] trailing him.<ref name=\"ThursAfternoon\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-thursday-pm-practice/|title=WDW: Thursday PM Practice|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 23, 1997}}</ref> One hour into the morning session, [[Davy Jones (racing driver)|Davy Jones]] was second fastest in front of [[Scott Goodyear]] when he lost control going into Turn 3 at 11.45 a.m. His car crashed rear first into the concrete wall, skidded across the track and pounded the inside wall. Jones was extricated and airlifted to [[Orlando Regional Medical Center]] in critical condition,<ref name=\"Thursday\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-thursday-practice-notes/|title=WDW: Thursday Practice Notes|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 23, 1997}}</ref> although he was upgraded to serious a few hours later.<ref name=\"Davy Jones Seriously Hurt In Wreck During Practice\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/24/sports/davy-jones-seriously-hurt-in-wreck-during-practice.html?scp=3&sq=1997%20Indy%20200&st=cse|title=Davy Jones Seriously Hurt In Wreck During Practice|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2009-07-02 | first=Joseph | last=Siano | date=January 24, 1997}}</ref> He suffered a closed head injury, as well as injuries in his neck's ligaments.<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216150302/http://brickyard.com:80/wdw/970124j.htm|title=Condition of Driver Davy Jones|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=February 7, 1997}}</ref> Jones underwent a lengthy and successful recovery, and would not race again until the [[1999 12 Hours of Sebring]]. On Friday morning, [[Galles Racing]] confirmed that their replacement driver would be [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]], a former motocross champion and [[Indy Lights]] regular who had not driven an Indy car since failing to qualify for the [[1995 Indianapolis 500]], and had not started an Indy car race.<ref name=\"Friday\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216154636/http://brickyard.com:80/wdw/970124c.htm|title=WDW Trackside Notes: Friday 1/24/97|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 24, 1997}}</ref>\n\n[[Tony Stewart]] completed his practice sweep by leading the morning session with a 167.046&nbsp;mph over [[Scott Sharp]] and [[Eddie Cheever]],<ref name=\"FridayFP\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-friday-am-practice-2008-03-27/|title=WDW: Friday AM Practice|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 24, 1997}}</ref> and confirmed his dominance on qualifying, where he scored the first pole of his IRL career with a best lap of 166.013&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"QualTimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-starting-grid-2008-03-27/?y=1997&s=1|title=WDW Starting Grid|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 23, 1997}}</ref> As expected, lap times were significantly slower than in the previous year, with a 15&nbsp;mph drop between [[Buddy Lazier]]'s pole from 1996 (181.388&nbsp;mph) and Stewart's, who was 1.8s slower in sheer lap time. Stewart didn't had as much margin as in practice, where he averaged an advantage of more than 3&nbsp;mph: three other drivers later went below the 22 second mark, with [[Arie Luyendyk]] being the closest of them all at 164.964&nbsp;mph, and [[Buzz Calkins]], who got out on track at the 11th hour after having fuel pressure issues, ended up 3rd, on what would be the best qualifying effort of his IRL career, in front of [[Scott Sharp]], [[Eddie Cheever]] and early favourite [[Scott Goodyear]]. [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] put his new ride in a solid 8th place, while the [[Infiniti]] drivers lagged behind: Lazier, who suffered a gearbox failure in the morning, managed to qualify 11th and points leader [[Mike Groff]] only ran faster than [[Jeret Schroeder]] and [[Danny Ongais]], who had no testing mileage whatsoever.<ref name=\"Friday\"/>\n\nThere were only 16 qualifiers, as three drivers had not had enough running to make an attempt: [[Roberto Guerrero]] had not run since suffering an oil system problem in his only test with the [[Infiniti]] engine on Wednesday, as a spare engine was not ready in time,<ref name=\"Friday\"/> while [[Jack Miller (driver)|Jack Miller]] (11 laps, best lap at 84&nbsp;mph) and [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]] (7 laps, 125&nbsp;mph) had not run a single lap at speed in their cars<ref name=\"FridayFP\"/> Guerrero and Miller were allowed to start the race at the back of the field, but Gr\u00e9goire was required to take part in the systems-check practice scheduled for Guerrero on raceday.<ref name=\"Friday\"/> Despite picking up a fuel problem, he got permission from USAC to start the race, where he parked the car after just two laps. [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]], who qualified in a career-best 10th place, also participated in the systems check after losing an engine on Friday afternoon practice, changing it for an \"Oldsmobile development engine\".<ref name=\"Raceday\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216154652/http://brickyard.com:80/wdw/970125a.htm|title=WDW Raceday Notes: Saturday 1/25/97|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 25, 1997}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Key\n! Meaning\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| Rookie\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">W</span>'''\n| Past winner\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \"style=fontsize=95%\"\n!| Pos\n!| No.\n!| Name\n!| Lap 1\n!| Lap 2\n!| Best (in&nbsp;mph)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| align=center| 2\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Tony Stewart]]\n| align=\"center\"| 21.760\n| align=\"center\"| 21.685 \n| align=\"center\"| 166.013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| align=center| 5\n| {{flagicon|NED}} [[Arie Luyendyk]]\n| align=\"center\"| 21.888\n| align=\"center\"| 21.823  \n| align=\"center\"| 164.964\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| align=center| 12\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Buzz Calkins]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">W</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 22.037\n| align=\"center\"| 21.945\n| align=\"center\"| 164.046\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| align=center| 1\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Scott Sharp]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.011\n| align=\"center\"| 21.980  \n| align=\"center\"| 163.785\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| align=center| 51\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Cheever]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.070\n| align=\"center\"| 22.012  \n| align=\"center\"| 163.547\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| align=center| 6\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Scott Goodyear]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.218\n| align=\"center\"| 22.041   \n| align=\"center\"| 163.332\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| align=center| 14\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Davey Hamilton]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.048\n| align=\"center\"| 22.172 \n| align=\"center\"| 163.280\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| align=center| 4\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 22.132\n| align=\"center\"| 22.317\n| align=\"center\"| 162.660\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| align=center| 27\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 22.185\n| align=\"center\"| 22.190  \n| align=\"center\"| 162.272 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| align=center| 33\n| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 22.379\n| align=\"center\"| 22.272  \n| align=\"center\"| 161.638 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| align=center| 91\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Buddy Lazier]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.418 \n| align=\"center\"| 22.313   \n| align=\"center\"| 161.341\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| align=center| 22\n| {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Marco Greco]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.671\n| align=\"center\"| 22.470 \n| align=\"center\"| 160.214\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| align=center| 18\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.563\n| align=\"center\"| 22.585\n| align=\"center\"| 159.553 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| align=center| 10\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Mike Groff]] \n| align=\"center\"| 22.591\n| align=\"center\"| 22.790   \n| align=\"center\"| 159.355\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| align=center| 30\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeret Schroeder]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 23.247\n| align=\"center\"| 23.565    \n| align=\"center\"| 154.859\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| align=center| 17\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Danny Ongais]]\n| align=\"center\"| 23.834\n| align=\"center\"| 23.765    \n| align=\"center\"| 151.483 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| align=center| 21\n| {{flagicon|COL}} [[Roberto Guerrero]]{{ref|1|1}}\n| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| Didn't qualify\n| align=\"center\"| No speed\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| align=center| 40\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jack Miller (driver)|Jack Miller]]{{ref|2|2}} '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| Didn't qualify\n| align=\"center\"| No speed\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| align=center| 77\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]]{{ref|2|2}}\n| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| Didn't qualify\n| align=\"center\"| No speed\n|}\n{{refbegin}}\n# {{note|1}} His engine had an oil system problem, and a spare was not ready on time. He was allowed to start the race at the back of the field.\n# {{note|2}} Elected not to qualify. He was allowed to start the race at the back of the field.\n{{refend}}\n\n====Failed to qualify or withdrew====\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Davy Jones (racing driver)|Davy Jones]] for [[Galles Racing]] - Replaced by {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''.\n\n===Race===\nRain fell in the early hours of the day, although the track was dried up 90 minutes before the start of the race. In a cool and cloudy Saturday morning, polesitter [[Tony Stewart]] ran away from the start, his pace not being matched by any of his competitors. [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] had a great start climbing to 5th place, while [[Eddie Cheever]] went the opposite way losing two additional spots to [[Scott Goodyear]] and a fast-starting [[Buddy Lazier]]. [[Buzz Calkins]] pressured [[Arie Luyendyk]] for second place and eventually passed him on Lap 15, pulling away shortly after. In fourth place, [[Scott Sharp]] lacked some pace, and started developing a loose condition around Lap 30. One of his corrections on Lap 32 made Ward lose the three spots he had gained, as he veered out to avoid an incident, and Stewart got to lap that group of cars by Lap 37, his lead having increased to 15 seconds. Sharp eventually started losing places, and had to do his first pit stop on Lap 45, much earlier than intended.<ref name=\"Raceday\"/>\n\nFrom around Lap 40, smoking was consistently reported out of Calkins' car while braking for Turn 1. Vapor chemtrails coming from the rear wings as a result of the high humidity also caused some confusing reports of smoking for other drivers, among them Stewart.<ref name=\"RaceReport\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-report/?y=1997&s=1|title=IRL: WDW report|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 25, 1997}}</ref> His first pit stop on Lap 65 was a slow one, depriving him of putting a lap on Calkins and Luyendyk. [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] had problems with his gearbox on his pit stop and slowed on track shortly after, having to retire from the race. After the first round of stops, Cheever was up to fourth place, having passed [[Scott Goodyear]] on track on Lap 50 and [[Buddy Lazier]] in the pit stop window. Running a race of his own, Stewart got around Luyendyk on Lap 79. Three laps later, [[Buzz Calkins]], who was bound to have the same fate, slowed on track after mistakenly turning off a switch in his car, trying to nurse his engine problems. He got back up to speed shortly after, in third place.\n\nLeading a pack of lapped cars in 13th place, six laps down, rookie [[Jeret Schroeder]] spun on his own on the exit of Turn 1 and crashed into the wall. The trail of cars that followed him slowed suddenly, and [[Arie Luyendyk]] lost control of his car trying to avoid them, crashing into the inside wall. Both incidents happened at reduced speeds, but the damage took both drivers out of the race, and caused a race-changing caution.<ref name=\"Raceday\"/> With rain looming in the background as a strong possibility, and the race being past the halfway point, most of the drivers elected to do an earlier second pit stop, hoping that rain appeared before Lap 170, with the exception of race leader [[Tony Stewart]], [[Marco Greco]] and [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]], who stuck to their two-stop strategy. Also, having stopped just before the caution, [[Scott Sharp]] restarted the race in front of [[Scott Goodyear]] and [[Buddy Lazier]], who passed the Canadian a few laps later, although Sharp would eventually lose position with both drivers within 30 laps.\n\nAfter his second green-flag pit stop on Lap 130, Stewart rejoined the track some 20 seconds behind [[Buzz Calkins]], and cautiosly let [[Eddie Cheever]] take second place while running on cold tires, getting by him again on Lap 143. Stewart was trying to make up a 10-second gap with the leader when, two laps later, Calkins slowed on track with a blown engine. That gave the lead back to Stewart, only for him to spun a few seconds later in Turn 3, damaging his rear wing and puncturing his right rear tire against the outside wall. It was thought that the spin had been caused by Stewart running into some debris from Calkins' blown engine, but he later stated that it had been caused by an oil leak in his car. Both drivers retired from the race while the caution was out, and heavy rain started falling on the track less than five minutes after their incidents.<ref name=\"Raceday\"/>\n\nIRL officials brought out the red flag on Lap 149. [[Eddie Cheever]] had inherited the lead during the caution, and would be later proclaimed as the winner after the race was called with 51 laps to go. This gave Cheever, who had not led a lap under green flag conditions, his first Indy car win after seven years, and the first for a driver-owner since [[A. J. Foyt]] at the [[1981 Pocono 500]]. It also ended a long winless drought in Cheever's career: it was his first win on any series since the [[1988 1000 km of Fuji]], his first win in an open-wheel car since the [[1979 European Formula Two Championship|1979 Formula 2]] race at [[Circuit Park Zandvoort|Zandvoort]], and the first major open-wheel victory of his career, having scored 9 podiums without a win in his ten-year F1 tenure, and another four in CART.\n\nDuring the caution, [[Buddy Lazier]], [[Scott Goodyear]] and [[Scott Sharp]] made a pit stop, but [[Mike Groff]], who had run ninth for most of the race, didn't follow suit, gaining three places on all of them for what would be the best finish of his career in second place, extending his championship lead to 10 points over [[Buzz Calkins]]. Also, Lazier's pit stop was significantly slower, which made him drop down to fifth place behind Goodyear and Sharp. [[Marco Greco]] got his third top 10 finish in a row with his two stop strategy, the same that propelled [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]] into his best result at that moment in sixth position in front of the unsung [[Davey Hamilton]]. Spaniard [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]] was the last running car in ninth place, in another career-best showing. Despite being credited with a 10th-place finish, [[Tony Stewart]] failed to see the checkered flag for the fifth IRL race in a row, having only finished a race in his first start at Orlando the previous year.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! Pos !! No. !! Driver !! Team !! Laps !! Time/Retired !! Grid !! Laps Led !! Points\n|-\n! 1\n| align=center|'''51'''\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Cheever]]\n|[[Cheever Racing|Team Cheever]]\n|align=center|149\n|al