nter|Accident\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|131\n|align=center|'''28'''\n|-\n! 11\n|align=center|'''12'''\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Buzz Calkins]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">W</span>'''\n|[[Bradley Motorsports]]\n|align=center|144\n|align=center|Engine\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|'''24'''\n|-\n! 12\n| align=center|'''5'''\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Arie Luyendyk]]\n|[[Treadway Racing]]\n|align=center|97\n|align=center|Accident\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''23'''\n|-\n! 13\n| align=center|'''17'''\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Danny Ongais]]\n|[[Chitwood Motorsports]]\n|align=center|94\n|align=center|Suspension\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''22'''\n|-\n! 14\n| align=center|'''30'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Jeret Schroeder]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''  &nbsp;&nbsp;\n|[[McCormack Motorsports]]\n|align=center|93\n|align=center|Accident\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''21'''\n|-\n! 15\n| align=center|'''40'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Jack Miller (driver)|Jack Miller]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n|[[Arizona Motorsport]]\n|align=center|85\n|align=center|Suspension\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''20'''\n|-\n! 16\n| align=center|'''4'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n|[[Galles Racing]]\n|align=center|63\n|align=center|Gearbox\n|align=center|8\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''19'''\n|-\n! 17\n| align=center|'''21'''\n|{{flagicon|COL}} [[Roberto Guerrero]]\n|[[Pagan Racing]]\n|align=center|56\n|align=center|Fuel Pump\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''18'''\n|-\n|-\n! 18\n| align=center|'''18'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]]\n|[[PDM Racing]]\n|align=center|46\n|align=center|Oil Pump\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''17'''\n|-\n! 19\n| align=center|'''77'''\n||{{flagicon|FRA}} [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]]\n|[[Chastain Motorsports]]\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|Fuel Pump\n|align=center|19\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''16'''\n|-\n|}\n\n==Race Statistics==\n*'''Lead changes:''' 3 among 3 drivers\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Lap Leaders\n|-\n! Laps\n! Leader\n|-\n|1-130 ||Tony Stewart\n|-\n|131-144 ||Buzz Calkins\n|-\n|145 ||Tony Stewart\n|-\n|146-149 ||Eddie Cheever\n|}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Cautions: 2 for 12 laps\n|-\n! Laps\n! Reason\n|-\n|99-106\n|Jeret Schroeder and Arie Luyendyk's crash\n|-\n|146-149\n|Tony Stewart crash / Rain\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Standings after the race==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Drivers' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Pos\n! Driver\n! Points\n|-\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Mike Groff]]\n| 96\n|-\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Buzz Calkins]]\n| 86\n|-\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Scott Sharp]]\n| 85\n|-\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Davey Hamilton]]\n| 82\n|-\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Marco Greco]]\n| 81\n|}\n\n* <small>'''Note:''' Only the top five positions are included for the standings.</small>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190824153451/https://www.indycar.com/ IndyCar official website]\n\n{{Walt Disney World Speedway IRL races}}\n\n{{American Championship Car race report footer |\n Series = Indy Racing League  |\n Name_of_race = {{nowrap|[[Walt Disney World Speedway|Indy 200 at Walt Disney World]] }}|\n Year_of_race = 1996-1997 |\n Previous_race_in_season = [[1996 Las Vegas 500K]] |\n Next_race_in_season = [[1997 Phoenix 200]] |\n Previous_year's_race = [[1996 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World]] |\n Next_year's_race = [[1998 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World]]\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indy 200 At Walt Disney World, 1997}}\n[[Category:1996\u201397 in IndyCar]]\n[[Category:1997 in sports in Florida|Indy 200 At Walt Disney World]]\n[[Category:Motorsport competitions in Florida|Walt Disney World]]\n[[Category:Events at Walt Disney World]]\n", "text_old": "{{American Championship Car race report infobox\n|Country       = USA\n|Race          = Walt Disney World\n|Image         = Walt_Disney_World_Speedway_diagram.svg\n|Date          = January 25\n|Year          = 1997\n|1996-1997     = yes\n|Official name = [[Delphi Indy 200|Indy 200 at Walt Disney World]]\n|Round_No      = 3rd\n|Series        = Indy Racing League\n|Location      = [[Walt Disney World Speedway]]\n|Course        = Permanent racing facility\n|Course_mi     = 1.000\n|Course_km     = 1.609\n|Distance_laps = 149\n|Distance_mi   = 149.000\n|Distance_km   = 239.792\n|Scheduled_laps = 200\n|Scheduled_mi   = 200.000\n|Scheduled_km   = 321.869\n|Weather       = Mixture of dry weather and rain; temperatures reaching up to {{convert|75.2|F|C}} along with wind speeds reaching up to {{convert|20|mph|km/h}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almanac.com/weather/history/zipcode/32821/1997-01-25 |title=''1997 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World'' weather information |publisher=Old Farmers' Almanac|accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>\n|Pole_Driver   = [[Tony Stewart]]\n|Pole_Team     = [[Team Menard]]\n|Pole_Time     = 21.685\n|Pole_Country  = USA\n|Fast_Driver   = [[Tony Stewart]]\n|Fast_Team     = [[Team Menard]]\n|Fast_Time     = 22.579\n|Fast_Lap      = 5\n|Fast_Country  = USA\n|First_Driver  = [[Eddie Cheever]]\n|First_Team    = [[Cheever Racing|Team Cheever]]\n|First_Country = USA\n|Second_Driver = [[Mike Groff]]\n|Second_Team   = [[Byrd-Cunningham Racing]]\n|Second_Country = USA\n|Third_Driver  = [[Scott Goodyear]]\n|Third_Team    = [[Treadway Racing]]\n|Third_Country = USA\n}}\n\nThe '''1997 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World''' was the third round of the [[1996\u20131997 in IRL|1996\u20131997 Indy Racing League]]. The race was held on January 25, 1997, at the {{convert|1.000|mi|km|abbr=on}} [[Walt Disney World Speedway]] in [[Bay Lake, Florida]], being the first IRL race of the calendar year 1997. It was the first race with the new chassis from [[Dallara]] and [[Panoz|G-Force]], as well as for the 4000 cc naturally aspirated engines supplied by [[Oldsmobile]] and [[Infiniti]], and it marked the first time that a major open-wheel series contested a race with brand-new cars and engines. The race was won by [[Eddie Cheever]] after being called off on lap 149 of the scheduled 200 due to heavy rain.<ref name=\"Lucky Victory Is Sweet To Star-Crossed Cheever\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/26/sports/lucky-victory-is-sweet-to-star-crossed-cheever.html?scp=4&sq=1997%20Indy%20200&st=cse|title=Lucky Victory Is Sweet To Star-Crossed Cheever|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2009-07-02 | first=Joseph | last=Siano | date=January 26, 1997}}</ref>\n\n==Report==\n===Pre-Race===\nThe Indy Racing League was faced with a four-month break between the second and third round, due to the nature of the 1996-97 calendar. This, combined with the addition of rounds at Texas and Pikes Peak that nullified a summer break, the criticism about the Indianapolis 500 overshadowing the co-championship of [[Buzz Calkins]] and [[Scott Sharp]],<ref name=\"CoChampions\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19961106105328/http://icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=14|title=News from the IRL - IRL starts new season|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=June 27, 1996}}</ref> and the majority of motorsport series and potential sponsors following a calendar-based approach, led the teams to complain about the split season.<ref name=\"IRL9697\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theautochannel.com/sports/openwheel/1022irl.html|title=IRL season will go with the normal calendar year|publisher=The Auto Channel|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 22, 1996}}</ref> On October 9, it was confirmed that the season would go beyond the Indianapolis 500, ending at the [[1997 Las Vegas 500K]], and that the series would switch to a calendar-based format for the 1998 season.<ref name=\"Calendar\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-seasons-to-change-to-claendar-years/|title=IRL: Seasons to change to calendar years|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 9, 1996}}</ref> Thus, the season schedule went from five to nine races. Following a successful test by [[Team Menard]] on September 25, with [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]] subbing for the injured [[Tony Stewart]] and [[Mark Dismore]]<ref name=\"CharlotteTest\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theautochannel.com/news/date/19961021/news02300.html|title=Looks Like There May Be an IRL Race at Charlotte in 1997|publisher=The Auto Channel|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 21, 1996}}</ref> with a fastest lap of 207.61&nbsp;mph, the IRL confirmed on December 17 a tenth round at [[Charlotte Motor Speedway]], to be held on July 26.<ref name=\"SunRace\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216163404/http://brickyard.com:80/irl/1996/96pr-061.htm|title=IRL heads to the heartland of Charlotte|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 17, 1996}}</ref>\n\nThe future of [[Tony Stewart]], who had his sights on a [[NASCAR]] ride and missed his [[Monster Energy NASCAR Cup Series|Winston Cup]] debut at Atlanta as a result of the injuries sustained at Las Vegas,<ref name=\"StewartStory\">{{cite news |url=https://www.racing-reference.info/showblog?id=2829|title=Tony Stewart's Planned Cup Debut|publisher=racing-reference.info|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 17, 2016}}</ref> was one of the big stories of the winter gap. Being only contracted with [[Team Menard]] through the original end of the season at Indianapolis,<ref name=\"MenardIndy\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090239/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=35|title=Stewart to run NASCAR, not IRL|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=September 20, 1996}}</ref> it was announced on September 17 that he would race full-time in the [[1997 NASCAR Winston Cup Series]] with his [[NASCAR Xfinity Series|Busch Series]] owner, [[Ranier Racing with MDM|Harry Ranier]].<ref name=\"StewartNASCAR\">{{cite news|url=https://articles.dailypress.com/1996-09-19/sports/9609190007_1_winston-cup-race-felix-sabates-robby-gordon|title=Stewart likely staying put|publisher=Daily Press|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=September 19, 1996}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, the deal fell through a month later, as a clause that estipulated that enough sponsorship for the full season had to be found by mid-October was not fulfilled.<ref name=\"StewartStory\"/><ref name=\"KOOL\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090204/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=39|title=IndyCar News - Who's Kool?|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 3, 1996}}</ref> During that month, it was reported that [[Andretti Autosport|Team Green]] tried to lure Stewart to its [[Kool (cigarette)|KOOL]]-backed CART operation for 1997,<ref name=\"KOOL\"/> and that [[General Motors]] wanted to get Stewart back from [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] by stablishing an IRL full-time operation centered around him with [[Hendrick Motorsports]], combined with a partial Busch Series schedule. However, Hendrick denied this information,<ref name=\"StewartStory\"/> and both negotiations were reported to have collapsed weeks later.<ref name=\"GreenNot\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090059/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=44|title=Team Green Looking Abroad|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 30, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"HendrickNot\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090026/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=46|title=Team Green still up in the air|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 15, 1996}}</ref>\n\nFrom September 30 to October 4, USAC organized a five-day test exclusively aimed at driver's tests, conducted with the [[PDM Racing]] 'mule' car. A total of 7 drivers passed their test, although only three of them would take part in an IRL race: [[Robbie Groff]], who had two IndyCar races under his belt, [[United States Auto Club#USAC Silver Crown Series|USAC Silver Crown]]  champion [[Jack Hewitt]] and [[ARCA Racing Series|ARCA]] champion and [[World of Outlaws]] race-winner [[Andy Hillenburg]]. The other four were [[1992 Atlantic Championship|Formula Atlantic]] champion [[Chris Smith (racing driver)|Chris Smith]], supermodified driver [[Mike Muldoon (racing driver)|Mike Muldoon]] and Silver Crown veterans [[Cary Faas]] and [[Jim Keeker]].<ref name=\"USACDrivers\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-phoenix-driver-testing-96-10-04/|title=Hewitt, Robbie Groff, 5 others pass IRL driver's tests|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 4, 1996}}</ref> [[IMSA GT Championship|IMSA]] regular [[Tom Hessert]] also passed his test on a conditional basis, and [[Butch Brickell]], recovered from the injuries sustained at [[Walt Disney World Speedway]], only passed two phases.<ref name=\"44Drivers\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216163708/http://brickyard.com:80/irl/1996/96pr-047.htm|title=USAC driver's tests made 44 drivers eligible for IRL competition|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 6, 1996}}</ref>\n\nDespite reports that the introduction of the new chassis and engine formula could be postponed, testing went ahead as scheduled.<ref name=\"Delay\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theautochannel.com/sports/openwheel/1022chassis.html|title=IRL chassis debut could be postponed|publisher=The Auto Channel|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 23, 1996}}</ref> With the [[Riley & Scott]] chassis being projected to debut at the Texas 500 after having been commissioned by [[Kelley Racing|Kelley Automotive Group]],<ref name=\"RileyScott\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-riley-scott-takes-first-irl-chassis-order/|title=Riley & Scott takes first IRL chassis order, plan competition debut in Longhorn 500|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=October 23, 1996}}</ref> whose initial plans were to resell the cars at a later date,<ref name=\"KelleySales\">{{cite news |url=http://www.news-sentinel.com/sports/top-sports/2015/05/21/hitting-the-bricksbrq-and-a-with-tom-kelley-brbrkelley-recalls-highs-and-lows-of-owning-a-racing-team/|title=Kelley recalls highs and lows of owning a racing team|publisher=[[Knoxville News Sentinel]]|accessdate=February 7, 2019|date=May 21, 2015}}</ref> the [[Panoz|G-Force]] chassis and the [[Oldsmobile]] engine made their debut at [[ISM Raceway|Phoenix]] on November 13\u201315 with [[Treadway Racing]] and [[Arie Luyendyk]] running 175 laps, and a best lap in the 162&nbsp;mph range.<ref name=\"GForceICR\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625090012/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=47|title=Luyendyk tests G-Force/Aurora IRL car|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 21, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"GForceMotorsport\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-phoenix-aurora-g-force-test/|title=Aurora V8 completes first track test|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 15, 1996}}</ref> [[Dallara]] did so on November 25\u201326 at [[Walt Disney World Speedway|Walt Disney World]] with [[Team Scandia]] and [[Eliseo Salazar]], who did 203 laps and a best lap of 157&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"DallaraICR\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625085951/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=48|title=Dallara runs at Disney World|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 29, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"DallaraBrickyard\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216163610/http://brickyard.com:80/irl/1996/96pr-051.htm|title=Salazar, Team Scandia complete first Dallara test|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=November 26, 1996}}</ref> However, by the time of the open test at Walt Disney World on December 10\u201313, [[Oldsmobile]]'s engine production had been scarce, and [[Infiniti]] was not ready to supply theirs.<ref name=\"InfinitiDelay\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625085929/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=49|title=Weekly News Update: Infiniti Delayed|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 4, 1996}}</ref> [[Arie Luyendyk]], [[Tony Stewart]] and [[Scott Sharp]] were the only drivers to take part, with Luyendyk setting a fastest lap of 166.898&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"TestWDW1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-testing-96-12-13/|title=Luyendyk sets top testing speed at 166.898&nbsp;mph at Walt Disney World|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 13, 1996}}</ref> Those tests were the first overseen by the new IRL executive director and vice president Leo Mehl, the former general manager for [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]].<ref name=\"Mehl\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-new-director-ims-staff-changes/|title=Tony George Announces New IRL Head and Additions To IMS Corporate Team |publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 2, 1996}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, the litigation between the IRL and CART regarding the use of the \"IndyCar\" trademark, and the one filled by [[A. J. Foyt]] for anti-competitive practices, ended in an out-of-court settlement \"without any acknowledgment of fault or liability by any party\".  CART agreed to end its licensing agreement with the [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway]] and cease use of the term \"IndyCar\" for their series, but its use by the IRL would be prohibited until 2003, as part of the settlement.<ref name=\"litigation\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-champcar-cart-cart-ims-litigation-ended/|title=CART and IMS Litigation Ended|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 17, 1996}}</ref> That same day, Joie Chitwood Jr. confirmed the formation of a new team, [[Chitwood Motorsports]], with veteran [[Danny Ongais]] as a driver,<ref name=\"Test 17-12\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-test-96-12-17/|title=Salazar Continues at Walt Disney World; Galles, Jones on Track at Phoenix|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 17, 1996}}</ref> and [[Treadway Racing]] followed suit by announcing [[Scott Goodyear]] as a driver for their second car, the two-time Indy 500 runner-up having only run partially in IndyCar for the last two years.<ref name=\"Goodyear\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-phoenix-test-96-12-18/|title=Salazar hits 164.285 miles per hour at Walt Disney World Speedway|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 18, 1996}}</ref> At the resuming of open tests at [[Walt Disney World Speedway]] from December 16\u201322, Goodyear led the proceedings with a 168.145&nbsp;mph lap. Stewart, Salazar, [[Eddie Cheever]], [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]] and [[Buzz Calkins]] also tested, while [[Galles Racing]] and [[Davy Jones (racing driver)|Davy Jones]] elected to do so at [[ISM Raceway|Phoenix International Raceway]].<ref name=\"TestOverall\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625085834/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=53|title=Goodyear Tops IRL Disney World Testing|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=December 24, 1996}}</ref>\n\nTesting at Orlando continued throughout the first weeks of January, with 10 drivers taking part, among them [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]] with [[Team Scandia]]. [[Tony Stewart]] put a best lap just south of the 170&nbsp;mph mark (169.795&nbsp;mph),<ref name=\"JanuaryTests\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970625085823/http://www.icr.com:80/cgi-win/webster2i.exe?4977%inputnewsId=54|title=Salazar Hurt at Disney World|publisher=IndyCar Magazine|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 17, 1997}}</ref> and [[Mike Groff]] debuted the [[Infiniti]] engine, getting close to 160&nbsp;mph in his best effort.<ref name=\"Groffiniti\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-test-97-01-15/|title=Groff, Byrd/Cunningham finish Nissan test; Hemelgarn, Lazier arrive at Walt Disney World Speedway|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 15, 1997}}</ref> They were joined by [[Buddy Lazier]], who got to do some system-check laps with the [[Infiniti]],<ref name=\"LazierInf\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216151020/http://brickyard.com:80/irl/97pr-009.htm|title=NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series haulers arrive; Lazier tests|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 16, 1997}}</ref> and Dr. [[Jack Miller (racing driver)|Jack Miller]], a veteran [[Indy Lights]] competitor who passed his rookie test in the [[PDM Racing]] 'mule' car. Miller, known as 'The Racing Dentist' for his full-time job, had arranged a deal with the [[Arizona Motorsports]] rental crew to race in 1997.<ref name=\"Test11\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-test-97-1-11/|title=Salazar hospitalized after testing accident|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 11, 1997}}</ref> On January 11, [[Eliseo Salazar]] lost control of his car after having an engine failure and crashed in Turn 1, suffering a compression fracture in his lower back.<ref name=\"Test11\"/> Salazar, injured at Orlando for the second year in a row, was ruled out of action \"at least until the beginning of May\".<ref name=\"Groffiniti\"/> On January 16, both [[Jeret Schroeder]], a [[U.S. F2000]] champion and top-5 contender in the [[Atlantic Championship]], and [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]] were confirmed to drive for [[McCormack Motorsports]] and Blueprint Racing, respectively.<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970617070115fw_/http://www.racelink.com/rl_news/archive/01_97/drn_wk3.html|title=RaceLink Daily Racing News - January 1997, Week 3|publisher=RaceLink.com|accessdate=February 7, 2019|date=January 16, 1997}}</ref><ref name=\"Test21\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-testing-97-01-21/|title=Lazier turns fastest Nissan-powered lap at 162.162; Schroeder passes rookie test, readies for Indy 200 weekend|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 21, 1997}}</ref>\n\n===Practice and qualifying===\n\nFurther testing was conducted on the week of the race with 11 drivers, among them [[Roberto Guerrero]] and [[Marco Greco]], designated by [[Team Scandia]] as Salazar's replacement.<ref name=\"Test20\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-testing-97-01-20/|title=Lazier tests Hemelgarn Dallara/Infiniti; teams start arriving for Indy 200 at Walt Disney World|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 20, 1997}}</ref> [[Tony Stewart]] logged the fastest lap at 165.975&nbsp;mph, with [[Buddy Lazier]] in close pursuit in his [[Infiniti]]-powered car.<ref name=\"Test22\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-testing-97-01-22/|title=Stewart tops among nine drivers on final winter testing day|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 22, 1997}}</ref> The entry list was unveiled on January 21 with 22 car/driver combinations, but [[Mark Dismore]], [[Robbie Buhl]] and [[Sam Schmidt]] were later withdrawn due to the widespread parts shortage that left them out of any winter testing.<ref name=\"Notes\"/> [[Davey Hamilton]] also had to skip winter testing for the same reason, but he remained entered nonetheless. The drivers already confirmed were joined by [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]] driving for a new team, [[Chastain Motorsports]].<ref name=\"Entry\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216154516/http://brickyard.com:80/wdw/97entry.htm|title=1997 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World, Tentative Entry List|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 21, 1997}}</ref> On Thursday, [[Stan Wattles]] announced his plans to become an driver-owner under the Metro Racing System banner he had driven with in Formula Atlantics. The deadline was set for a late 1997 start at the earliest, in anticipation of a full-season effort in 1998.\n\nThursday practice was dominated by [[Tony Stewart]], who led with a 167.715&nbsp;mph lap in the morning session<ref name=\"ThursMorning\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-thursday-am-practice/|title=WDW: Thursday AM Practice|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 23, 1997}}</ref> and a 165.738&nbsp;mph lap in the afternoon, with [[Buzz Calkins]] and [[Buddy Lazier]] trailing him.<ref name=\"ThursAfternoon\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-thursday-pm-practice/|title=WDW: Thursday PM Practice|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 23, 1997}}</ref> One hour into the morning session, [[Davy Jones (racing driver)|Davy Jones]] was second fastest in front of [[Scott Goodyear]] when he lost control going into Turn 3 at 11.45 a.m. His car crashed rear first into the concrete wall, skidded across the track and pounded the inside wall. Jones was extricated and airlifted to [[Orlando Regional Medical Center]] in critical condition,<ref name=\"Thursday\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-thursday-practice-notes/|title=WDW: Thursday Practice Notes|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 23, 1997}}</ref> although he was upgraded to serious a few hours later.<ref name=\"Davy Jones Seriously Hurt In Wreck During Practice\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/01/24/sports/davy-jones-seriously-hurt-in-wreck-during-practice.html?scp=3&sq=1997%20Indy%20200&st=cse|title=Davy Jones Seriously Hurt In Wreck During Practice|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=2009-07-02 | first=Joseph | last=Siano | date=January 24, 1997}}</ref> He suffered a closed head injury, as well as injuries in his neck's ligaments.<ref name=\"Jones\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216150302/http://brickyard.com:80/wdw/970124j.htm|title=Condition of Driver Davy Jones|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=February 7, 1997}}</ref> Jones underwent a lengthy and successful recovery, and would not race again until the [[1999 12 Hours of Sebring]]. On Friday morning, [[Galles Racing]] confirmed that their replacement driver would be [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]], a former motocross champion and [[Indy Lights]] regular who had not driven an Indy car since failing to qualify for the [[1995 Indianapolis 500]], and had not started an Indy car race.<ref name=\"Friday\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216154636/http://brickyard.com:80/wdw/970124c.htm|title=WDW Trackside Notes: Friday 1/24/97|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 24, 1997}}</ref>\n\n[[Tony Stewart]] completed his practice sweep by leading the morning session with a 167.046&nbsp;mph over [[Scott Sharp]] and [[Eddie Cheever]],<ref name=\"FridayFP\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-friday-am-practice-2008-03-27/|title=WDW: Friday AM Practice|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 24, 1997}}</ref> and confirmed his dominance on qualifying, where he scored the first pole of his IRL career with a best lap of 166.013&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"QualTimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-starting-grid-2008-03-27/?y=1997&s=1|title=WDW Starting Grid|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 23, 1997}}</ref> As expected, lap times were significantly slower than in the previous year, with a 15&nbsp;mph drop between [[Buddy Lazier]]'s pole from 1996 (181.388&nbsp;mph) and Stewart's, who was 1.8s slower in sheer lap time. Stewart didn't had as much margin as in practice, where he averaged an advantage of more than 3&nbsp;mph: three other drivers later went below the 22 second mark, with [[Arie Luyendyk]] being the closest of them all at 164.964&nbsp;mph, and [[Buzz Calkins]], who got out on track at the 11th hour after having fuel pressure issues, ended up 3rd, on what would be the best qualifying effort of his IRL career, in front of [[Scott Sharp]], [[Eddie Cheever]] and early favourite [[Scott Goodyear]]. [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] put his new ride in a solid 8th place, while the [[Infiniti]] drivers lagged behind: Lazier, who suffered a gearbox failure in the morning, managed to qualify 11th and points leader [[Mike Groff]] only ran faster than [[Jeret Schroeder]] and [[Danny Ongais]], who had no testing mileage whatsoever.<ref name=\"Friday\"/>\n\nThere were only 16 qualifiers, as three drivers had not had enough running to make an attempt: [[Roberto Guerrero]] had not run since suffering an oil system problem in his only test with the [[Infiniti]] engine on Wednesday, as a spare engine was not ready in time,<ref name=\"Friday\"/> while [[Jack Miller (driver)|Jack Miller]] (11 laps, best lap at 84&nbsp;mph) and [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]] (7 laps, 125&nbsp;mph) had not run a single lap at speed in their cars<ref name=\"FridayFP\"/> Guerrero and Miller were allowed to start the race at the back of the field, but Gr\u00e9goire was required to take part in the systems-check practice scheduled for Guerrero on raceday.<ref name=\"Friday\"/> Despite picking up a fuel problem, he got permission from USAC to start the race, where he parked the car after just two laps. [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]], who qualified in a career-best 10th place, also participated in the systems check after losing an engine on Friday afternoon practice, changing it for an \"Oldsmobile development engine\".<ref name=\"Raceday\">{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970216154652/http://brickyard.com:80/wdw/970125a.htm|title=WDW Raceday Notes: Saturday 1/25/97|publisher=Indy Racing League|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 25, 1997}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Key\n! Meaning\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| Rookie\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">W</span>'''\n| Past winner\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \"style=fontsize=95%\"\n!| Pos\n!| No.\n!| Name\n!| Lap 1\n!| Lap 2\n!| Best (in&nbsp;mph)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 1\n| align=center| 2\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Tony Stewart]]\n| align=\"center\"| 21.760\n| align=\"center\"| 21.685 \n| align=\"center\"| 166.013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 2\n| align=center| 5\n| {{flagicon|NED}} [[Arie Luyendyk]]\n| align=\"center\"| 21.888\n| align=\"center\"| 21.823  \n| align=\"center\"| 164.964\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 3\n| align=center| 12\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Buzz Calkins]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">W</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 22.037\n| align=\"center\"| 21.945\n| align=\"center\"| 164.046\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 4\n| align=center| 1\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Scott Sharp]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.011\n| align=\"center\"| 21.980  \n| align=\"center\"| 163.785\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 5\n| align=center| 51\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Cheever]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.070\n| align=\"center\"| 22.012  \n| align=\"center\"| 163.547\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 6\n| align=center| 6\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Scott Goodyear]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.218\n| align=\"center\"| 22.041   \n| align=\"center\"| 163.332\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 7\n| align=center| 14\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Davey Hamilton]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.048\n| align=\"center\"| 22.172 \n| align=\"center\"| 163.280\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 8\n| align=center| 4\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 22.132\n| align=\"center\"| 22.317\n| align=\"center\"| 162.660\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 9\n| align=center| 27\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 22.185\n| align=\"center\"| 22.190  \n| align=\"center\"| 162.272 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 10\n| align=center| 33\n| {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 22.379\n| align=\"center\"| 22.272  \n| align=\"center\"| 161.638 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| align=center| 91\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Buddy Lazier]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.418 \n| align=\"center\"| 22.313   \n| align=\"center\"| 161.341\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 12\n| align=center| 22\n| {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Marco Greco]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.671\n| align=\"center\"| 22.470 \n| align=\"center\"| 160.214\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 13\n| align=center| 18\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]]\n| align=\"center\"| 22.563\n| align=\"center\"| 22.585\n| align=\"center\"| 159.553 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 14\n| align=center| 10\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Mike Groff]] \n| align=\"center\"| 22.591\n| align=\"center\"| 22.790   \n| align=\"center\"| 159.355\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 15\n| align=center| 30\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeret Schroeder]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| align=\"center\"| 23.247\n| align=\"center\"| 23.565    \n| align=\"center\"| 154.859\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 16\n| align=center| 17\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Danny Ongais]]\n| align=\"center\"| 23.834\n| align=\"center\"| 23.765    \n| align=\"center\"| 151.483 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 17\n| align=center| 21\n| {{flagicon|COL}} [[Roberto Guerrero]]{{ref|1|1}}\n| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| Didn't qualify\n| align=\"center\"| No speed\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| align=center| 40\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jack Miller (driver)|Jack Miller]]{{ref|2|2}} '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| Didn't qualify\n| align=\"center\"| No speed\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| align=center| 77\n| {{flagicon|FRA}} [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]]{{ref|2|2}}\n| colspan=2 align=\"center\"| Didn't qualify\n| align=\"center\"| No speed\n|}\n{{refbegin}}\n# {{note|1}} His engine had an oil system problem, and a spare was not ready on time. He was allowed to start the race at the back of the field.\n# {{note|2}} Elected not to qualify. He was allowed to start the race at the back of the field.\n{{refend}}\n\n====Failed to qualify or withdrew====\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Davy Jones (racing driver)|Davy Jones]] for [[Galles Racing]] - Replaced by {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''.\n\n===Race===\nRain fell in the early hours of the day, although the track was dried up 90 minutes before the start of the race. In a cool and cloudy Saturday morning, polesitter [[Tony Stewart]] ran away from the start, his pace not being matched by any of his competitors. [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] had a great start climbing to 5th place, while [[Eddie Cheever]] went the opposite way losing two additional spots to [[Scott Goodyear]] and a fast-starting [[Buddy Lazier]]. [[Buzz Calkins]] pressured [[Arie Luyendyk]] for second place and eventually passed him on Lap 15, pulling away shortly after. In fourth place, [[Scott Sharp]] lacked some pace, and started developing a loose condition around Lap 30. One of his corrections on Lap 32 made Ward lose the three spots he had gained, as he veered out to avoid an incident, and Stewart got to lap that group of cars by Lap 37, his lead having increased to 15 seconds. Sharp eventually started losing places, and had to do his first pit stop on Lap 45, much earlier than intended.<ref name=\"Raceday\"/>\n\nFrom around Lap 40, smoking was consistently reported out of Calkins' car while braking for Turn 1. Vapor chemtrails coming from the rear wings as a result of the high humidity also caused some confusing reports of smoking for other drivers, among them Stewart.<ref name=\"RaceReport\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motorsport.com/indycar/news/irl-wdw-report/?y=1997&s=1|title=IRL: WDW report|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=April 2, 2018|date=January 25, 1997}}</ref> His first pit stop on Lap 65 was a slow one, depriving him of putting a lap on Calkins and Luyendyk. [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] had problems with his gearbox on his pit stop and slowed on track shortly after, having to retire from the race. After the first round of stops, Cheever was up to fourth place, having passed [[Scott Goodyear]] on track on Lap 50 and [[Buddy Lazier]] in the pit stop window. Running a race of his own, Stewart got around Luyendyk on Lap 79. Three laps later, [[Buzz Calkins]], who was bound to have the same fate, slowed on track after mistakenly turning off a switch in his car, trying to nurse his engine problems. He got back up to speed shortly after, in third place.\n\nLeading a pack of lapped cars in 13th place, six laps down, rookie [[Jeret Schroeder]] spun on his own on the exit of Turn 1 and crashed into the wall. The trail of cars that followed him slowed suddenly, and [[Arie Luyendyk]] lost control of his car trying to avoid them, crashing into the inside wall. Both incidents happened at reduced speeds, but the damage took both drivers out of the race, and caused a race-changing caution.<ref name=\"Raceday\"/> With rain looming in the background as a strong possibility, and the race being past the halfway point, most of the drivers elected to do an earlier second pit stop, hoping that rain appeared before Lap 170, with the exception of race leader [[Tony Stewart]], [[Marco Greco]] and [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]], who stuck to their two-stop strategy. Also, having stopped just before the caution, [[Scott Sharp]] restarted the race in front of [[Scott Goodyear]] and [[Buddy Lazier]], who passed the Canadian a few laps later, although Sharp would eventually lose position with both drivers within 30 laps.\n\nAfter his second green-flag pit stop on Lap 130, Stewart rejoined the track some 20 seconds behind [[Buzz Calkins]], and cautiosly let [[Eddie Cheever]] take second place while running on cold tires, getting by him again on Lap 143. Stewart was trying to make up a 10-second gap with the leader when, two laps later, Calkins slowed on track with a blown engine. That gave the lead back to Stewart, only for him to spun a few seconds later in Turn 3, damaging his rear wing and puncturing his right rear tire against the outside wall. It was thought that the spin had been caused by Stewart running into some debris from Calkins' blown engine, but he later stated that it had been caused by an oil leak in his car. Both drivers retired from the race while the caution was out, and heavy rain started falling on the track less than five minutes after their incidents.<ref name=\"Raceday\"/>\n\nIRL officials brought out the red flag on Lap 149. [[Eddie Cheever]] had inherited the lead during the caution, and would be later proclaimed as the winner after the race was called with 51 laps to go. This gave Cheever, who had not led a lap under green flag conditions, his first Indy car win after seven years, and the first for a driver-owner since [[A. J. Foyt]] at the [[1981 Pocono 500]]. It also ended a long winless drought in Cheever's career: it was his first win on any series since the [[1988 1000 km of Fuji]], his first win in an open-wheel car since the [[1979 European Formula Two Championship|1979 Formula 2]] race at [[Circuit Park Zandvoort|Zandvoort]], and the first major open-wheel victory of his career, having scored 9 podiums without a win in his ten-year F1 tenure, and another four in CART.\n\nDuring the caution, [[Buddy Lazier]], [[Scott Goodyear]] and [[Scott Sharp]] made a pit stop, but [[Mike Groff]], who had run ninth for most of the race, didn't follow suit, gaining three places on all of them for what would be the best finish of his career in second place, extending his championship lead to 10 points over [[Buzz Calkins]]. Also, Lazier's pit stop was significantly slower, which made him drop down to fifth place behind Goodyear and Sharp. [[Marco Greco]] got his third top 10 finish in a row with his two stop strategy, the same that propelled [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]] into his best result at that moment in sixth position in front of the unsung [[Davey Hamilton]]. Spaniard [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]] was the last running car in ninth place, in another career-best showing. Despite being credited with a 10th-place finish, [[Tony Stewart]] failed to see the checkered flag for the fifth IRL race in a row, having only finished a race in his first start at Orlando the previous year.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! Pos !! No. !! Driver !! Team !! Laps !! Time/Retired !! Grid !! Laps Led !! Points\n|-\n! 1\n| align=center|'''51'''\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Cheever]]\n|[[Cheever Racing|Team Cheever]]\n|align=center|149\n|align=center|1:06:43.145\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|'''35'''\n|-\n! 2\n| align=\"center\"|'''10'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Mike Groff]]\n|[[Byrd-Cunningham Racing]]\n|align=center|149\n|align=center|+ 51.278 sec\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''33'''\n|-\n! 3\n| align=center|'''6'''\n|{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Scott Goodyear]]\n|[[Treadway Racing]]\n|align=center|149\n|align=center|+ 54.803 sec\n|align=center|6\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''32'''\n|-\n! 4\n| align=center|'''1'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Scott Sharp]]\n|[[A. J. Foyt Enterprises]]\n|align=center|149\n|align=center|+ 55.506 sec\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''31'''\n|-\n! 5\n|align=center|'''91'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Buddy Lazier]]\n|[[Hemelgarn Racing]]\n|align=center|149\n|align=center|+ 56.162 sec\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''30'''\n|-\n! 6\n| align=center |'''27'''\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jim Guthrie (racing driver)|Jim Guthrie]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n|[[Blueprint Racing]]\n|align=center|148\n|align=center|+ 1 lap\n|align=center|9\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''29'''\n|-\n! 7\n|align=\"center\" |'''14'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Davey Hamilton]]\n|[[A. J. Foyt Enterprises]]\n|align=center|148\n|align=center|+ 1 lap\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''28'''\n|-\n! 8\n| align=center|'''22'''\n|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Marco Greco]]\n|[[Team Scandia]]\n|align=center|147\n|align=center|+ 2 laps\n|align=center|12\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''27'''\n|-\n! 9\n| align=center|'''33'''\n||{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Ferm\u00edn V\u00e9lez]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n|[[Team Scandia]]\n|align=center|147\n|align=center|+ 2 laps\n|align=center|10\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''26'''\n|-\n! 10\n| align=center|'''2'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Tony Stewart]]\n|[[Team Menard]]\n|align=center|146\n|align=center|Accident\n|align=center|1\n|align=center|131\n|align=center|'''28'''\n|-\n! 11\n|align=center|'''12'''\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Buzz Calkins]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:gold;\">W</span>'''\n|[[Bradley Motorsports]]\n|align=center|144\n|align=center|Engine\n|align=center|3\n|align=center|14\n|align=center|'''24'''\n|-\n! 12\n| align=center|'''5'''\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Arie Luyendyk]]\n|[[Treadway Racing]]\n|align=center|97\n|align=center|Accident\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''23'''\n|-\n! 13\n| align=center|'''17'''\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Danny Ongais]]\n|[[Chitwood Motorsports]]\n|align=center|94\n|align=center|Suspension\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''22'''\n|-\n! 14\n| align=center|'''30'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Jeret Schroeder]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''  &nbsp;&nbsp;\n|[[McCormack Motorsports]]\n|align=center|93\n|align=center|Accident\n|align=center|15\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''21'''\n|-\n! 15\n| align=center|'''40'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Jack Miller (driver)|Jack Miller]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n|[[Arizona Motorsport]]\n|align=center|85\n|align=center|Suspension\n|align=center|18\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''20'''\n|-\n! 16\n| align=center|'''4'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[Jeff Ward (motorsports)|Jeff Ward]] '''<span style=\"padding:1px 4px; color:black; background-color:yellowgreen;\">R</span>'''\n|[[Galles Racing]]\n|align=center|63\n|align=center|Gearbox\n|align=center|8\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''19'''\n|-\n! 17\n| align=center|'''21'''\n|{{flagicon|COL}} [[Roberto Guerrero]]\n|[[Pagan Racing]]\n|align=center|56\n|align=center|Fuel Pump\n|align=center|17\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''18'''\n|-\n|-\n! 18\n| align=center|'''18'''\n|{{flagicon|US}} [[John Paul Jr. (racing driver)|John Paul Jr.]]\n|[[PDM Racing]]\n|align=center|46\n|align=center|Oil Pump\n|align=center|13\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''17'''\n|-\n! 19\n| align=center|'''77'''\n||{{flagicon|FRA}} [[St\u00e9phan Gr\u00e9goire]]\n|[[Chastain Motorsports]]\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|Fuel Pump\n|align=center|19\n|align=center|0\n|align=center|'''16'''\n|-\n|}\n\n==Race Statistics==\n*'''Lead changes:''' 3 among 3 drivers\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Lap Leaders\n|-\n! Laps\n! Leader\n|-\n|1-130 ||Tony Stewart\n|-\n|131-144 ||Buzz Calkins\n|-\n|145 ||Tony Stewart\n|-\n|146-149 ||Eddie Cheever\n|}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Cautions: 2 for 12 laps\n|-\n! Laps\n! Reason\n|-\n|99-106\n|Jeret Schroeder and Arie Luyendyk's crash\n|-\n|146-149\n|Tony Stewart crash / Rain\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Standings after the race==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Drivers' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! Pos\n! Driver\n! Points\n|-\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Mike Groff]]\n| 96\n|-\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Buzz Calkins]]\n| 86\n|-\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Scott Sharp]]\n| 85\n|-\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|US}} [[Davey Hamilton]]\n| 82\n|-\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Marco Greco]]\n| 81\n|}\n\n* <small>'''Note:''' Only the top five positions are included for the standings.</small>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190824153451/https://www.indycar.com/ IndyCar official website]\n\n{{Walt Disney World Speedway IRL races}}\n\n{{American Championship Car race report footer |\n Series = Indy Racing League  |\n Name_of_race = {{nowrap|[[Walt Disney World Speedway|Indy 200 at Walt Disney World]] }}|\n Year_of_race = 1996-1997 |\n Previous_race_in_season = [[1996 Las Vegas 500K]] |\n Next_race_in_season = [[1997 Phoenix 200]] |\n Previous_year's_race = [[1996 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World]] |\n Next_year's_race = [[1998 Indy 200 at Walt Disney World]]\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indy 200 At Walt Disney World, 1997}}\n[[Category:1996\u201397 in IndyCar]]\n[[Category:1997 in sports in Florida|Indy 200 At Walt Disney World]]\n[[Category:Motorsport competitions in Florida|Walt Disney World]]\n[[Category:Events at Walt Disney World]]\n", "name_user": "MasterAlSpain", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePre-Race", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Indy_200_at_Walt_Disney_World"}
{"title_page": "Marsh wren", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Marsh wren\n| image = Cistothorus palustris -Reifel Island, Vancouver-8.jpg\n| image_caption = in Canada<br/>\n[[File: Cistothorus palustris - Marsh Wren - XC105805.ogg |thumb|center|Singing in ''[[Typha]]'' marsh in Minnesota ]]\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22711374/0 |title=''Cistothorus palustris'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Cistothorus\n| species = palustris\n| authority = ([[Alexander Wilson (ornithologist)|Wilson, A.]], 1810)\n| synonyms =\n''Telmatodytes palustris''\n| range_map = Cistothorus palustris map.svg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution map\n{{Leftlegend|orange|Breeding}}\n{{Leftlegend|yellow|Migration}}\n{{Leftlegend|purple|Resident}}\n{{Leftlegend|blue|Non-breading}}\n}}\n\nThe '''marsh wren''' (''Cistothorus palustris'') is a small [[North America]]n [[songbird]] of the [[wren]] [[family (biology)|family]]. It is sometimes called '''long-billed marsh wren''' to distinguish it from the [[sedge wren]], also known as short-billed marsh wren.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe marsh wren was [[Species description|described]] by the Scottish-American ornithologist [[Alexander Wilson (ornithologist)|Alexander Wilson]] in 1810 and given the [[binomial name]] ''Certhia palustris''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Wilson | first=Alexander | author-link= Alexander Wilson (ornithologist) | year=1810 | title= American ornithology, or, The natural history of the birds of the United States | volume=Volume 2 | place=Philadelphia | publisher=Bradford and Inskeep | pages=58\u201360 , Plate 12 fig. 4 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/46337236 }}</ref> The current [[genus]] ''[[Cistothorus]]'' was introduced by the German ornithologist [[Jean Cabanis]] in 1850.<ref>{{ cite book | last= Cabanis | first=Jean | author-link=Jean Cabanis | year=1850 | title= Museum Heineanum : Verzeichniss der ornithologischen Sammlung des Oberamtmann Ferdinand Heine, auf Gut St. Burchard vor Halberstadt | volume=Volume 1 | language=German | place=Halbertstadt  | publisher=In Commission bei R. Frantz | page=77 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/49584456 }}</ref> There are 15 recognised [[subspecies]].<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2017 | title=Dapple-throats, sugarbirds, fairy-bluebirds, kinglets, hyliotas, wrens & gnatcatchers | work=World Bird List Version 7.3 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/sugarbirds/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=29 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nEtymology: From Greek '\u03ba\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2' (''cistos'', \"a shrub\") and '\u03b8\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2' (''thouros'', \"leaping, or running through\") and Latin 'palustris' (\"marshy\"). <ref>{{cite book |last1=McGillivray, Semenchuck |first1=William Bruce, Glen Peter |title=The Federation of Alberta Naturalists Field Guide to Alberta Birds |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1u9JDa7eKmoC&pg=PA222&lpg=PA222&dq=cistothorus+etymology#v=onepage |website=Google Books |year=1998 |publisher=Federation of Alberta Naturalists |isbn=9780969613428 |accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Cistothorus palustris CT.jpg|thumb|left|[[Cap Tourmente National Wildlife Area]], Quebec, Canada]]\n\nAdults have brown upperparts with a light brown belly and flanks and a white throat and breast. The back is black with white stripes. They have a dark cap with a white line over the eyes and a short thin bill.\n\nThe male's song is a loud gurgle used to declare ownership of territory; western males have a more varied repertoire.\n\nThis little bird is native to Canada, Mexico, and the United States. Their breeding habitat is [[marsh]]es with tall vegetation such as [[cattail]]s across [[North America]]. In the western United States, some birds are permanent residents. Other birds [[bird migration|migrate]] to marshes and salt marshes in the southern United States and [[Mexico]]. their non-breeding range is in the southern United States going into Mexico and their breeding range is in the northeastern United States going into Canada.<ref>Cornell All About Birds. https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Marsh_Wren/lifehistory</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== Foraging and Diet ==\nThese birds forage actively in vegetation close to the water, occasionally flying up to catch [[insect]]s in flight. They mainly eat insects, also [[spider]]s and [[snail]]s. In California, 53 Western Marsh Wren stomachs were examined which showed that the birds consume bugs (29%), caterpillars and chrysalids (17%), beetles (16%), ants and wasps (8%), spiders (5%), carabids and coccinellids  (2%), with various other flies, grasshoppers, dragonflies and unidentifiable insect remains making up over 11 percent. Ants and wasps were observed to be mostly eaten in the fall. <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Marsh_Wren/lifehistory|title=Marsh Wren|last=|first=|date=|website=All About Birds|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book|last=Beal|first=F. E. L|title=Birds of California in relation to the fruit industry|publisher=Washington Government Printing Office|year=1907|isbn=|volume=Part 1|location=|pages=62}}</ref>\n\n== Nesting ==\nThe [[bird nest|nest]] is an oval structure attached to marsh vegetation, entered from the side. The male builds many unused nests in his territory. A hypothesis of the possible reason to why males build multiple \"dummy\" nests in their territory is that they are courting areas and that the females construct the \"breeding nest\", where she lays the eggs in.<ref>Metz, Karen J. \u201cThe Enigma of Multiple Nest Building by Male Marsh Wrens.\u201d Jan. 1991, pp. 170\u2013173.</ref> He may puncture the eggs and fatally peck the nestlings of other birds nesting nearby, including his own species (even his own offspring) and [[red-winged blackbird]]s, [[yellow-headed blackbird]]s, and [[least bittern]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/308|title=Marsh Wren (''Cistothorus palustris'')|last1=Kroodsma|first1=Donald E.|last2=Verner|first2=Jared|year=1997|editor=A. Poole|work=The Birds of North America Online|publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology|accessdate=2013-03-03}}</ref> The [[clutch (eggs)|clutch]] is normally four to six [[bird egg|eggs]], though the number can range from three to ten.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Marsh_Wren_dtl.html |title=All About Birds: Marsh Wren |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |accessdate=2008-07-20}}</ref> The eggs are usually 0.6-0.7 inches in length and 0.4-0.6 inches in width<ref name=\":0\" />. Incubation is performed only by females, and only females develop a brood patch. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Verner|first=Jared|title=Breeding Biology of the Long-billed Marsh Wren|publisher=|year=1964|isbn=|location=|pages=19}}</ref>Marsh wren young can get infected by pathogenic larvae.<ref>Warren, Yvonne. \u201cProtocalliphora Braueri (Diptera: Calliphoridae) Induced Pathogenesis in a Brood of Marsh Wren (Cistothorus Palustris) Young.\u201d Journal of Wildlife Diseases, 17 Mar. 1993, www.jwildlifedis.org/doi/10.7589/0090-3558-30.1.107.</ref> The Blowfly larvae infect the young by subdermal myiasis-induced lesions and subsequent sepsis.<ref>Warren, Yvonne. \u201cProtocalliphora Braueri (Diptera: Calliphoridae) Induced Pathogenesis in a Brood of Marsh Wren (Cistothorus Palustris) Young.\u201d Journal of Wildlife Diseases, 17 Mar. 1993, www.jwildlifedis.org/doi/10.7589/0090-3558-30.1.107.</ref> The larvae form a wound in the young by rasping and expanding a hole in their skin to create blood flow and feed on the blood of the hosts' body.<ref>Warren, Yvonne. \u201cProtocalliphora Braueri (Diptera: Calliphoridae) Induced Pathogenesis in a Brood of Marsh Wren (Cistothorus Palustris) Young.\u201d Journal of Wildlife Diseases, 17 Mar. 1993, www.jwildlifedis.org/doi/10.7589/0090-3558-30.1.107.</ref>  \n\n== Conservation ==\nThis bird is still common with an estimated global breeding population of 9.4 million.<ref name=\":0\" /> That being said, its numbers have declined with the loss of suitable wetland habitat and wholesale draining of marshes will lead to local extinction. Still, this [[species]] is widespread enough not to qualify as threatened according to the [[IUCN]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:MarshWrenTuleLake.jpg|Marsh Wren at Tule Lake National Wildlife Refuge, California\nFile:Cistothorus palustris Iona.jpg|Iona, British Columbia, Canada\nFile:100 Marsh Wren cropped.jpg|Nest, illustration\nFile:Museum of Science, Boston, MA - IMG 3236.JPG|Eggs\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Henninger, W.F. (1906): A preliminary list of the birds of Seneca County, Ohio. ''[[Wilson Bulletin|Wilson Bull.]]'' '''18'''(2): 47\u201360. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606161911/http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Wilson/DJVU/v018n02/P0047-P0060.djvu DjVu fulltext] [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606161920/http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Wilson/v018n02/p0047-p0060.pdf PDF fulltext]\n* Warren, Yvonne. \u201cProtocalliphora Braueri (Diptera: Calliphoridae) Induced Pathogenesis in a Brood of Marsh Wren (Cistothorus Palustris) Young.\u201d Journal of Wildlife Diseases, 17 Mar. 1993, www.jwildlifedis.org/doi/10.7589/0090-3558-30.1.107.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{ cite journal | last1=Luttrell | first1=Sarah A.M.  | last2=Lohr | first2=Bernard | year=2018 | title=Geographic variation in call structure, likelihood, and call-song associations across subspecies boundaries, migratory patterns, and habitat types in the Marsh Wren (''Cistothorus palustris'') | journal=The Auk | volume=135 | issue=1 | pages=127\u2013151 | doi= 10.1642/AUK-17-110.1 | doi-access=free }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cistothorus palustris|the marsh wren}}\n{{Wikispecies|Cistothorus palustris}}\n*[http://www.mbr-pwrc.usgs.gov/id/framlst/i7250id.html Identification tips] - USGS Patuxent Bird Identification InfoCenter\n* {{InternetBirdCollection|marsh-wren-cistothorus-palustris|Marsh wren}}\n* {{VIREO|Marsh+Wren|Marsh wren}}\n* {{IUCN_Map|22711374|Cistothorus palustris}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1379530}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:wren, marsh}}\n[[Category:Cistothorus|marsh wren]]\n[[Category:Birds of North America]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1810|marsh wren]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Alexander Wilson (ornithologist)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| name = Marsh wren\n| image = Cistothorus palustris -Reifel Island, Vancouver-8.jpg\n| image_caption = in Canada<br/>\n[[File: Cistothorus palustris - Marsh Wren - XC105805.ogg |thumb|center|Singing in ''[[Typha]]'' marsh in Minnesota ]]\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22711374/0 |title=''Cistothorus palustris'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Cistothorus\n| species = palustris\n| authority = ([[Alexander Wilson (ornithologist)|Wilson, A.]], 1810)\n| synonyms =\n''Telmatodytes palustris''\n| range_map = Cistothorus palustris map.svg\n| range_map_caption = Distribution map\n{{Leftlegend|orange|Breeding}}\n{{Leftlegend|yellow|Migration}}\n{{Leftlegend|purple|Resident}}\n{{Leftlegend|blue|Non-breading}}\n}}\n\nThe '''marsh wren''' (''Cistothorus palustris'') is a small [[North America]]n [[songbird]] of the [[wren]] [[family (biology)|family]]. It is sometimes called '''long-billed marsh wren''' to distinguish it from the [[sedge wren]], also known as short-billed marsh wren.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe marsh wren was [[Species description|described]] by the Scottish-American ornithologist [[Alexander Wilson (ornithologist)|Alexander Wilson]] in 1810 and given the [[binomial name]] ''Certhia palustris''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Wilson | first=Alexander | author-link= Alexander Wilson (ornithologist) | year=1810 | title= American ornithology, or, The natural history of the birds of the United States | volume=Volume 2 | place=Philadelphia | publisher=Bradford and Inskeep | pages=58\u201360 , Plate 12 fig. 4 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/46337236 }}</ref> The current [[genus]] ''[[Cistothorus]]'' was introduced by the German ornithologist [[Jean Cabanis]] in 1850.<ref>{{ cite book | last= Cabanis | first=Jean | author-link=Jean Cabanis | year=1850 | title= Museum Heineanum : Verzeichniss der ornithologischen Sammlung des Oberamtmann Ferdinand Heine, auf Gut St. Burchard vor Halberstadt | volume=Volume 1 | language=German | place=Halbertstadt  | publisher=In Commission bei R. Frantz | page=77 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/49584456 }}</ref> There are 15 recognised [[subspecies]].<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2017 | title=Dapple-throats, sugarbirds, fairy-bluebirds, kinglets, hyliotas, wrens & gnatcatchers | work=World Bird List Version 7.3 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/sugarbirds/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=29 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nEtymology: From Greek '\u03ba\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2' (''cistos'', \"a shrub\") and '\u03b8\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2' (''thouros'', \"leaping, or running through\") and Latin 'palustris' (\"marshy\"). <ref>{{cite book |last1=McGillivray, Semenchuck |first1=William Bruce, Glen Peter |title=The Federation of Alberta Naturalists Field Guide to Alberta Birds |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1u9JDa7eKmoC&pg=PA222&lpg=PA222&dq=cistothorus+etymology#v=onepage |website=Google Books |year=1998 |publisher=Federation of Alberta Naturalists |isbn=9780969613428 |accessdate=22 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Cistothorus palustris CT.jpg|thumb|left|[[Cap Tourmente National Wildlife Area]], Quebec, Canada]]\n\nAdults have brown upperparts with a light brown belly and flanks and a white throat and breast. The back is black with white stripes. They have a dark cap with a white line over the eyes and a short thin bill.\n\nThe male's song is a loud gurgle used to declare ownership of territory; western males have a more varied repertoire.\n\nThis little bird is native to Canada, Mexico, and the United States. Their breeding habitat is [[marsh]]es with tall vegetation such as [[cattail]]s across [[North America]]. In the western United States, some birds are permanent residents. Other birds [[bird migration|migrate]] to marshes and salt marshes in the southern United States and [[Mexico]]. their non-breeding range is in the southern United States going into Mexico and their breeding range is in the northeastern United States going into Canada.<ref>Cornell All About Birds. https://www.allaboutbirds.org/guide/Marsh_Wren/lifehistory</ref>\n\nThese birds forage actively in vegetation, sometimes flying up to catch [[insect]]s in flight. They mainly eat insects, also [[spider]]s and [[snail]]s.\n\nThe [[bird nest|nest]] is an oval structure attached to marsh vegetation, entered from the side. The [[clutch (eggs)|clutch]] is normally four to six [[bird egg|eggs]], though the number can range from three to ten.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/BirdGuide/Marsh_Wren_dtl.html |title=All About Birds: Marsh Wren |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |accessdate=2008-07-20}}</ref> The male builds many unused nests in his territory. A hypothesis of the possible reason to why males build multiple \"dummy\" nests in their territory is that they are courting areas and that the females construct the \"breeding nest\", where she lays the eggs in.<ref>Metz, Karen J. \u201cThe Enigma of Multiple Nest Building by Male Marsh Wrens.\u201d Jan. 1991, pp. 170\u2013173.</ref> He may puncture the eggs and fatally peck the nestlings of other birds nesting nearby, including his own species (even his own offspring) and [[red-winged blackbird]]s, [[yellow-headed blackbird]]s, and [[least bittern]]s.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/308 | last1 = Kroodsma | first1 = Donald E. | last2 = Verner | first2 = Jared | year = 1997 | title = Marsh Wren (''Cistothorus palustris'') | work = The Birds of North America Online | editor = A. Poole | publisher = Cornell Lab of Ornithology | accessdate = 2013-03-03}}</ref>\nMarsh wren young can get infected by pathogenic larvae.<ref>Warren, Yvonne. \u201cProtocalliphora Braueri (Diptera: Calliphoridae) Induced Pathogenesis in a Brood of Marsh Wren (Cistothorus Palustris) Young.\u201d Journal of Wildlife Diseases, 17 Mar. 1993, www.jwildlifedis.org/doi/10.7589/0090-3558-30.1.107.</ref> The Blowfly larvae infect the young by subdermal myiasis-induced lesions and subsequent sepsis.<ref>Warren, Yvonne. \u201cProtocalliphora Braueri (Diptera: Calliphoridae) Induced Pathogenesis in a Brood of Marsh Wren (Cistothorus Palustris) Young.\u201d Journal of Wildlife Diseases, 17 Mar. 1993, www.jwildlifedis.org/doi/10.7589/0090-3558-30.1.107.</ref> The larvae form a wound in the young by rasping and expanding a hole in their skin to create blood flow and feed on the blood of the hosts' body.<ref>Warren, Yvonne. \u201cProtocalliphora Braueri (Diptera: Calliphoridae) Induced Pathogenesis in a Brood of Marsh Wren (Cistothorus Palustris) Young.\u201d Journal of Wildlife Diseases, 17 Mar. 1993, www.jwildlifedis.org/doi/10.7589/0090-3558-30.1.107.</ref>  \nThis bird is still common, although its numbers have declined with the loss of suitable wetland habitat. Wholesale draining of marshes will lead to local extinction. Still, this [[species]] is widespread enough not to qualify as threatened according to the [[IUCN]].\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:MarshWrenTuleLake.jpg|Marsh Wren at Tule Lake National Wildlife Refuge, California\nFile:Cistothorus palustris Iona.jpg|Iona, British Columbia, Canada\nFile:100 Marsh Wren cropped.jpg|Nest, illustration\nFile:Museum of Science, Boston, MA - IMG 3236.JPG|Eggs\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Henninger, W.F. (1906): A preliminary list of the birds of Seneca County, Ohio. ''[[Wilson Bulletin|Wilson Bull.]]'' '''18'''(2): 47\u201360. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606161911/http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Wilson/DJVU/v018n02/P0047-P0060.djvu DjVu fulltext] [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606161920/http://elibrary.unm.edu/sora/Wilson/v018n02/p0047-p0060.pdf PDF fulltext]\n* Warren, Yvonne. \u201cProtocalliphora Braueri (Diptera: Calliphoridae) Induced Pathogenesis in a Brood of Marsh Wren (Cistothorus Palustris) Young.\u201d Journal of Wildlife Diseases, 17 Mar. 1993, www.jwildlifedis.org/doi/10.7589/0090-3558-30.1.107.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{ cite journal | last1=Luttrell | first1=Sarah A.M.  | last2=Lohr | first2=Bernard | year=2018 | title=Geographic variation in call structure, likelihood, and call-song associations across subspecies boundaries, migratory patterns, and habitat types in the Marsh Wren (''Cistothorus palustris'') | journal=The Auk | volume=135 | issue=1 | pages=127\u2013151 | doi= 10.1642/AUK-17-110.1 | doi-access=free }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Cistothorus palustris|the marsh wren}}\n{{Wikispecies|Cistothorus palustris}}\n*[http://www.mbr-pwrc.usgs.gov/id/framlst/i7250id.html Identification tips] - USGS Patuxent Bird Identification InfoCenter\n* {{InternetBirdCollection|marsh-wren-cistothorus-palustris|Marsh wren}}\n* {{VIREO|Marsh+Wren|Marsh wren}}\n* {{IUCN_Map|22711374|Cistothorus palustris}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1379530}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:wren, marsh}}\n[[Category:Cistothorus|marsh wren]]\n[[Category:Birds of North America]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1810|marsh wren]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Alexander Wilson (ornithologist)]]\n", "name_user": "Rishi aeleti 891", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reformatting, additions in diet, reproduction and conservation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marsh_wren"}
{"title_page": "Ugric languages", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[Ugri\u0107]], a river in Bosnia, and [[Oghuric languages]]}}\n{{More footnotes|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox language family|name=Ugric|altname=Ugrian|acceptance=controversial|region=[[Hungary]] and Western [[Siberia]]|familycolor=Uralic|fam2=[[Finno-Ugric languages|Finno-Ugric]]|glotto=none|child1=''[[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]''|child2=''[[Khanty language|Khanty]]''|child3=''[[Mansi language|Mansi]]''|map=Lenguas_ugrias.png|mapcaption=The Ugric languages}}\n\nThe '''Ugric''' or '''Ugrian''' languages ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|\u0261|r|\u1d7b|k}} or {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|\u0261|r|i|\u0259|n}}), are a proposed branch of the [[Uralic languages|Uralic]] [[language family]]. The name Ugric is derived from [[Ugrians]], an archaic exonym for the [[Magyars]] (Hungarians) and [[Yugra]], a region in north-west Russia. \n\nUgric includes three subgroups: [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], [[Khanty language|Khanty]], and [[Mansi language|Mansi]]. The last two have traditionally been considered single languages, though their main dialects are sufficiently distinct that they may also be considered small subfamilies of three to four languages each. A common '''Proto-Ugric language''' is posited to have been spoken from the end of the 3rd&nbsp;millennium&nbsp;BC until the first half of the 1st&nbsp;millennium&nbsp;BC, in Western [[Siberia]], east of the southern [[Ural mountains]]. Of the three languages, Khanty and Mansi have traditionally been set apart from Hungarian as [[Ob-Ugric languages|Ob-Ugric]], though features uniting Mansi and Hungarian in particular are known as well.\n\n==Phonetic development==\n\n===Consonants===\nTwo common phonetic features of the Ugric languages are a rearrangement of the [[Proto-Uralic]] (PU) system of [[sibilant consonant]]s and a lenition of [[velar consonant]]s:<ref name = \"Sml88\">{{citation\n| last = Sammallahti\n| first = Pekka\n| author-link = Pekka Sammallahti\n| year = 1988\n| chapter = Historical phonology of the Uralic languages, with special reference to Samoyed, Ugric, and Permic\n| title = The Uralic Languages: Description, History and Foreign Influences\n| editor = Denis Sinor\n| pages = 478\u2013554\n| publisher = Brill\n| publication-place = Leiden\n}}</ref>\n* PU *s and *[[\u0161]] merged and developed into a non-sibilant sound (possibly {{IPA|[\u03b8]}} or [[\u026c|{{IPA|[\u026c]}}]]), yielding Mansi /t/, Khanty *[[\u026c]] \u2192 /t/ or /l/ (depending on dialect), and lost in Hungarian.\n* PU *[[\u015b]] depalatalized to *s.\n* PU medial *x, *k, *w generally lenited to *[[\u0263]].\nIt has however been pointed out that these changes are applicable to the [[Samoyedic languages]] as well.<ref>{{cite journal |author=H\u00e4kkinen, Jaakko |year=2009 |title=Kantauralin ajoitus ja paikannus: perustelut puntarissa |journal=Suomalais-Ugrilaisen Seuran Aikakauskirja |volume=92 |url=http://www.sgr.fi/susa/92/hakkinen.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe consonant cluster *lm is in the Ugric languages mostly reduced to plain {{IPA|/m/}} (e.g. PU [[wiktionary:Appendix:Proto-Uralic/\u015bilm\u00e4|*\u015bilm\u00e4]] 'eye' \u2192 Hungarian ''szem'', Mansi \u0441\u0430\u043c {{IPA|/sam/}}, Khanty \u0441\u0435\u043c {{IPA|/sem/}}). A peculiar exception is the numeral '3', in which Hungarian (''h\u00e1rom'') and Mansi (\u0445\u0443\u0440\u044d\u043c {{IPA|/xu\u02d0r\u0259m/}}) point to an original cluster *rm, whereas the rest of the Uralic family suggests original *lm (Khanty \u0445\u043e\u043b\u04d9\u043c, Finnish ''kolme'', Estonian ''kolm'', Inari Sami ''kulma'', Erzya \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043c\u043e, etc.) This has frequently been listed as an argument for considering Hungarian more closely related to Mansi than Khanty. The reverse has also been suggested\u2014Hungarian and Mansi retaining the original form of the numeral, whereas Khanty and all the [[Finno-Permic languages]] would have innovated {{IPA|/l/}} for some reason.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Janhunen |first=Juha |authorlink=Juha Janhunen |title=Proto-Uralic \u2013 what, where and when? |year=2009 |journal=Suomalais-Ugrilaisen Seuran toimituksia |volume=258 |isbn=978-952-5667-11-0 |issn=0355-0230 |url=http://www.sgr.fi/sust/sust258/sust258_janhunen.pdf |format=pdf}}</ref>\n\nHungarian and the current literary standard Mansi and Khanty all share a spirantization of Proto-Uralic *k to {{IPA|/h/}} or {{IPA|/x/}} before [[back vowel]]s, e.g. 'fish': PU [[wiktionary:Appendix:Proto-Uralic/kala|*kala]] \u2192 Hungarian ''hal'', Mansi \u0445\u0443\u043b {{IPA|/xu\u02d0l/}}, Khanty \u0445\u0443\u043b {{IPA|/xul/}}. This is itself not a common Ugric feature \u2014 {{IPA|/k/}} remains in other Mansi and Khanty dialects (e.g. Eastern Khanty {{IPA|/kul/}}, Southern Mansi {{IPA|/ko\u02d0l/}} 'fish'), but it has been argued to result from a proto-Ugric split of *k to front and back allophones {{IPA|[k]}} ~ {{IPA|[q]}}, with the latter then independently spirantizing in each three cases.\n\nThe three Ugric varieties also share the lateralization of Proto-Uralic *[[\u03b4]] to *l (as do the [[Permic languages]]), but it is possible this postcedes the emergence of retroflex *[[\u026d]] from PU *l in Khanty.<ref name = \"Sml88\"/> Another possible counterargument is the similar lateralization of the palatalized counterpart *\u03b4\u0301 \u2192 Mansi {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}}, likely to have been a simultaneous change with the lateralization of *[[\u00f0]]. In Khanty the reflex is {{IPA|/j/}}, whereas instances of {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}} also exist, which may suggest a separate development. An original *[[\u013a]] is no longer reconstructed for older stages of Uralic, however, which leaves the origin of Khanty {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}} an open question.\n\nAn innovation clearly limited to the Ugric languages is the development of *[[\u014b]] to *\u014bk, though there are numerous exceptions in each language to this.\n\n===Vowels===\nThe development of the vowel system remains subject to interpretation. All three Ugric branches contrast [[vowel length]]; in Hungarian this is late, generally derived by [[compensatory lengthening]] after loss of unstressed vowels and *\u0263. The Ob-Ugric languages, however, derive their quantity contrasts mainly from PU quality contrasts: thus for example in Northern Mansi, PU [[wiktionary:Appendix:Proto-Uralic/pelj\u00e4|*pelj\u00e4]] 'ear' \u2192 *p\u00e4\u013a \u2192 {{IPA|/pal\u02b2/}}, but PU [[wiktionary:Appendix:Proto-Uralic/p\u00e4l\u00e4|*p\u00e4l\u00e4]] 'half' \u2192 *p\u00e4\u00e4l \u2192 {{IPA|/pa\u02d0l/}}.\n\nContrasts between PU stem vowels (*a/*\u00e4 vs. *i) do not survive as such in modern Ugric languages, but they commonly leave their mark on vowel qualities in the first syllable, suggesting retention of the contrast at least to the Proto-Ugric stage. For example, PU *\u0144'''\u00ef'''xl'''i''' 'arrow' \u2192 Hungarian ''ny\u00edl'', but PU *m'''\u00ef'''ks'''a''' 'liver' \u2192 Hungarian ''m\u00e1j''. Remnants of original stem vowels are also found in the oldest Hungarian records, such as PU *konta 'group, hunting party' \u2192 Old Hungarian ''hodu'' 'army' (\u2192 Modern Hungarian ''had'').\n\n==Lexical features==\nThe Ugric languages share considerable amounts of common lexicon not found in the other Uralic languages. This includes both basic vocabulary, e.g. 'fire' (Hungarian ''t\u0171z'', Mansi \u0442\u0430\u045e\u0442 /ta\u02d0wt/, Khanty \u0442\u0443\u0442 /tut/) as well as more specialized terminology, particularly the word for 'horse' (H ''l\u00f3, lov-'', M \u043b\u0443\u045e /luw/, Kh \u043b\u0430\u0432 /law/) and related items such as 'saddle' (H ''nyer\u00ebg'', M \u043d\u0430\u0433\u044d\u0440 /na\u0263\u0259r/). This latter fact together with an importance of horse motifs in Ob-Ugric folklore has been used to argue for locating Proto-Ugric in the southernmost parts of Siberia, in close contact with nomadic steppe peoples if not nomadic themselves. Some loanwords from such sources into Ugric are known as well, perhaps most prominently the numeral '7': *\u03b8\u00e4pt(V) \u2192 H ''h\u00e9t'',{{efn|The initial /h/ is unetymological, and has been explained as influence of the adjacent numeral ''hat'' '6'.}} M \u0441\u0430\u0442 /sat/, Kh \u0442\u0430\u043f\u04d9\u0442 /tap\u0259t/ (from an [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] source; cf. [[Sanskrit]] ''sapt\u00e1'', [[Avestan]] ''hapta'', both from [[Proto-Indo-Iranian language|Proto-Indo-Iranian]] ''*sapt\u00e1'' < [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] ''{{PIE|*sept\u1e3f\u0325}}'').\n\n''Names'' of two of the Ugric peoples are cognate as well: Hungarian ''magyar'' 'Hungarian' can be equated with ''Mansi'' (from an original root *m\u00e4\u0144\u0107-). A related word in Khanty denotes a specific [[phratry]].\n\nA common derivational innovation is seen in the word for 'louse': Proto-Uralic *t\u00e4ji \u2192 *t\u00e4(j)-ktVmV \u2192 H ''tet\u0171'', M \u0442\u0430\u043a\u044d\u043c, Kh \u0442\u0435\u0432\u0442\u04d9\u043c.\n\n==Structural features==\n* An original [[ablative]] case marked by ''-l''\n* A series of original [[locative]] cases, formed from postpositions derived from a pronoun root ''*n\u00e4''\n* [[Possessive suffix]]es are placed before [[case suffix]]es, not after them as in the other Uralic languages\n* A class of \"instable\" verb stems, in which alternation between CV and CVC stem variants occurs, e.g. ''to take': Hungarian ''v\u00eb-'' ~ ''v\u00ebv-'' ~ ''[[wiktionary:vesz|v\u00ebsz-]]'', Mansi *wi- ~ *w\u00e6j-, Khanty *w\u0115- ~ *w\u0115j-.\n* Distinct attributive and nominal forms of the numeral '2': Hungarian ''[[wiktionary:k\u00e9t|k\u00e9t]]'' vs. ''[[wiktionary:kett\u0151|kett\u0151]]'', Mansi \u043a\u0438\u0442 vs. \u043a\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0433, Khanty (Northern) \u043a\u0430\u0442 vs. \u043a\u0430\u0442\u04d9\u043d, (Eastern) {{IPA|/k\u00e6t/}} vs. {{IPA|/k\u00e6t\u0259\u0263/}}\n* Found in Hungarian and Mansi, an extended form of the [[caritive]] suffix containing ''-l''.\n* Distinct verb conjugations according to the [[transitivity (grammatical category)|transitivity]] of the verb. It is sometimes termed as \u201cdefinite\u201d versus \u201cindefinite\u201d conjugation, because also the [[definiteness]] of the [[Object (grammar)|object]] can play a role when selecting between the two. This feature is within the Uralic family also found in the [[Mordvinic languages]], and it is likely to not represent a common Ugric innovation; the particular details of the construction are different in all three Ugric languages.\n* Verbal prefixes, which modify the meaning of the verb in both concrete and abstract ways\n\n;Examples from Mansi\n\n\u0113l(a) \u2013 'forwards, onwards, away'\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| j\u014dm- 'to go, to stride' || \u0113l-j\u014dm- 'to go away/on'\n|-\n| tinal- 'to sell' || \u0113l-tinal- 'to sell off'\n|}\n\nxot \u2013 'direction away from something and other nuances of action intensity'\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| min- 'to go' || xot-min- 'to go away, to stop'\n|-\n| roxt- 'to be frightened' || xot-roxt- 'to take fright suddenly'\n|}\n\n;Examples from Hungarian\n\nel \u2013 'away, off'\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| ugrik 'to jump' || elugrik 'to jump away'\n|-\n| mosolyog 'to smile' || elmosolyodik 'to start to smile' (implying a lack of control)\n|}\n\nki \u2013 'out (of)'\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| ugrik 'to jump' || kiugrik 'to jump out'\n|-\n| n\u00e9z 'to look' || kin\u00e9z 'to look out'\n|}\n\nIn Hungarian, the [[citation form]] of verbs is the present tense of the 3rd person singular form, which is given here, which does not have any suffixes.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Uralic languages]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|1}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n*{{cite journal|last=Honti|first=L\u00e1szl\u00f3|title=Features of Ugric Languages (Observations on the Question of Ugric Unity)|year=1979|pages=1\u201325|volume=29|journal=Acta Linguistica Academia Scientiarum Hungaricae}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Honti|first=L\u00e1szl\u00f3|title=Ugrilainen kantakieli \u2013 erheellinen vai reaalinen hypoteesi?|year=1998|volume=228|journal=Suomalais-Ugrilaisen Seuran toimituksia|isbn=952-5150-15-1}}\n*{{cite book |last=Riese |first=Timothy |title=Vogul: Languages of the World/Materials 158 |url=http://www.lincom.at |publisher=Lincom Europa |year=2001 |isbn=3-89586-231-2}}\n*{{cite book |last=T\u00f6rkenczy |first=Mikl\u00f3s |title=Hungarian Verbs & Essentials of Grammar |publisher=Passport Books |year=1997 |isbn=0-8442-8350-9}}\n\n{{Uralic languages}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Uralic languages]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=[[Ugri\u0107]], a river in Bosnia, and [[Oghuric languages]]}}\n{{More footnotes|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox language family|name=Ugric|altname=Ugrian|acceptance=controversial|region=[[Hungary]] and Western [[Siberia]]|familycolor=Uralic|fam2=|glotto=none|child1=''[[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]''|child2=''[[Khanty language|Khanty]]''|child3=''[[Mansi language|Mansi]]''|map=Lenguas_ugrias.png|mapcaption=The Ugric languages}}\n\nThe '''Ugric''' or '''Ugrian''' languages ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|\u0261|r|\u1d7b|k}} or {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|ju\u02d0|\u0261|r|i|\u0259|n}}), are a proposed branch of the [[Uralic languages|Uralic]] [[language family]]. The name Ugric is derived from [[Ugrians]], an archaic exonym for the [[Magyars]] (Hungarians) and [[Yugra]], a region in north-west Russia. \n\nUgric includes three subgroups: [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]], [[Khanty language|Khanty]], and [[Mansi language|Mansi]]. The last two have traditionally been considered single languages, though their main dialects are sufficiently distinct that they may also be considered small subfamilies of three to four languages each. A common '''Proto-Ugric language''' is posited to have been spoken from the end of the 3rd&nbsp;millennium&nbsp;BC until the first half of the 1st&nbsp;millennium&nbsp;BC, in Western [[Siberia]], east of the southern [[Ural mountains]]. Of the three languages, Khanty and Mansi have traditionally been set apart from Hungarian as [[Ob-Ugric languages|Ob-Ugric]], though features uniting Mansi and Hungarian in particular are known as well.\n\n==Phonetic development==\n\n===Consonants===\nTwo common phonetic features of the Ugric languages are a rearrangement of the [[Proto-Uralic]] (PU) system of [[sibilant consonant]]s and a lenition of [[velar consonant]]s:<ref name = \"Sml88\">{{citation\n| last = Sammallahti\n| first = Pekka\n| author-link = Pekka Sammallahti\n| year = 1988\n| chapter = Historical phonology of the Uralic languages, with special reference to Samoyed, Ugric, and Permic\n| title = The Uralic Languages: Description, History and Foreign Influences\n| editor = Denis Sinor\n| pages = 478\u2013554\n| publisher = Brill\n| publication-place = Leiden\n}}</ref>\n* PU *s and *[[\u0161]] merged and developed into a non-sibilant sound (possibly {{IPA|[\u03b8]}} or [[\u026c|{{IPA|[\u026c]}}]]), yielding Mansi /t/, Khanty *[[\u026c]] \u2192 /t/ or /l/ (depending on dialect), and lost in Hungarian.\n* PU *[[\u015b]] depalatalized to *s.\n* PU medial *x, *k, *w generally lenited to *[[\u0263]].\nIt has however been pointed out that these changes are applicable to the [[Samoyedic languages]] as well.<ref>{{cite journal |author=H\u00e4kkinen, Jaakko |year=2009 |title=Kantauralin ajoitus ja paikannus: perustelut puntarissa |journal=Suomalais-Ugrilaisen Seuran Aikakauskirja |volume=92 |url=http://www.sgr.fi/susa/92/hakkinen.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe consonant cluster *lm is in the Ugric languages mostly reduced to plain {{IPA|/m/}} (e.g. PU [[wiktionary:Appendix:Proto-Uralic/\u015bilm\u00e4|*\u015bilm\u00e4]] 'eye' \u2192 Hungarian ''szem'', Mansi \u0441\u0430\u043c {{IPA|/sam/}}, Khanty \u0441\u0435\u043c {{IPA|/sem/}}). A peculiar exception is the numeral '3', in which Hungarian (''h\u00e1rom'') and Mansi (\u0445\u0443\u0440\u044d\u043c {{IPA|/xu\u02d0r\u0259m/}}) point to an original cluster *rm, whereas the rest of the Uralic family suggests original *lm (Khanty \u0445\u043e\u043b\u04d9\u043c, Finnish ''kolme'', Estonian ''kolm'', Inari Sami ''kulma'', Erzya \u043a\u043e\u043b\u043c\u043e, etc.) This has frequently been listed as an argument for considering Hungarian more closely related to Mansi than Khanty. The reverse has also been suggested\u2014Hungarian and Mansi retaining the original form of the numeral, whereas Khanty and all the [[Finno-Permic languages]] would have innovated {{IPA|/l/}} for some reason.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Janhunen |first=Juha |authorlink=Juha Janhunen |title=Proto-Uralic \u2013 what, where and when? |year=2009 |journal=Suomalais-Ugrilaisen Seuran toimituksia |volume=258 |isbn=978-952-5667-11-0 |issn=0355-0230 |url=http://www.sgr.fi/sust/sust258/sust258_janhunen.pdf |format=pdf}}</ref>\n\nHungarian and the current literary standard Mansi and Khanty all share a spirantization of Proto-Uralic *k to {{IPA|/h/}} or {{IPA|/x/}} before [[back vowel]]s, e.g. 'fish': PU [[wiktionary:Appendix:Proto-Uralic/kala|*kala]] \u2192 Hungarian ''hal'', Mansi \u0445\u0443\u043b {{IPA|/xu\u02d0l/}}, Khanty \u0445\u0443\u043b {{IPA|/xul/}}. This is itself not a common Ugric feature \u2014 {{IPA|/k/}} remains in other Mansi and Khanty dialects (e.g. Eastern Khanty {{IPA|/kul/}}, Southern Mansi {{IPA|/ko\u02d0l/}} 'fish'), but it has been argued to result from a proto-Ugric split of *k to front and back allophones {{IPA|[k]}} ~ {{IPA|[q]}}, with the latter then independently spirantizing in each three cases.\n\nThe three Ugric varieties also share the lateralization of Proto-Uralic *[[\u03b4]] to *l (as do the [[Permic languages]]), but it is possible this postcedes the emergence of retroflex *[[\u026d]] from PU *l in Khanty.<ref name = \"Sml88\"/> Another possible counterargument is the similar lateralization of the palatalized counterpart *\u03b4\u0301 \u2192 Mansi {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}}, likely to have been a simultaneous change with the lateralization of *[[\u00f0]]. In Khanty the reflex is {{IPA|/j/}}, whereas instances of {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}} also exist, which may suggest a separate development. An original *[[\u013a]] is no longer reconstructed for older stages of Uralic, however, which leaves the origin of Khanty {{IPA|/l\u02b2/}} an open question.\n\nAn innovation clearly limited to the Ugric languages is the development of *[[\u014b]] to *\u014bk, though there are numerous exceptions in each language to this.\n\n===Vowels===\nThe development of the vowel system remains subject to interpretation. All three Ugric branches contrast [[vowel length]]; in Hungarian this is late, generally derived by [[compensatory lengthening]] after loss of unstressed vowels and *\u0263. The Ob-Ugric languages, however, derive their quantity contrasts mainly from PU quality contrasts: thus for example in Northern Mansi, PU [[wiktionary:Appendix:Proto-Uralic/pelj\u00e4|*pelj\u00e4]] 'ear' \u2192 *p\u00e4\u013a \u2192 {{IPA|/pal\u02b2/}}, but PU [[wiktionary:Appendix:Proto-Uralic/p\u00e4l\u00e4|*p\u00e4l\u00e4]] 'half' \u2192 *p\u00e4\u00e4l \u2192 {{IPA|/pa\u02d0l/}}.\n\nContrasts between PU stem vowels (*a/*\u00e4 vs. *i) do not survive as such in modern Ugric languages, but they commonly leave their mark on vowel qualities in the first syllable, suggesting retention of the contrast at least to the Proto-Ugric stage. For example, PU *\u0144'''\u00ef'''xl'''i''' 'arrow' \u2192 Hungarian ''ny\u00edl'', but PU *m'''\u00ef'''ks'''a''' 'liver' \u2192 Hungarian ''m\u00e1j''. Remnants of original stem vowels are also found in the oldest Hungarian records, such as PU *konta 'group, hunting party' \u2192 Old Hungarian ''hodu'' 'army' (\u2192 Modern Hungarian ''had'').\n\n==Lexical features==\nThe Ugric languages share considerable amounts of common lexicon not found in the other Uralic languages. This includes both basic vocabulary, e.g. 'fire' (Hungarian ''t\u0171z'', Mansi \u0442\u0430\u045e\u0442 /ta\u02d0wt/, Khanty \u0442\u0443\u0442 /tut/) as well as more specialized terminology, particularly the word for 'horse' (H ''l\u00f3, lov-'', M \u043b\u0443\u045e /luw/, Kh \u043b\u0430\u0432 /law/) and related items such as 'saddle' (H ''nyer\u00ebg'', M \u043d\u0430\u0433\u044d\u0440 /na\u0263\u0259r/). This latter fact together with an importance of horse motifs in Ob-Ugric folklore has been used to argue for locating Proto-Ugric in the southernmost parts of Siberia, in close contact with nomadic steppe peoples if not nomadic themselves. Some loanwords from such sources into Ugric are known as well, perhaps most prominently the numeral '7': *\u03b8\u00e4pt(V) \u2192 H ''h\u00e9t'',{{efn|The initial /h/ is unetymological, and has been explained as influence of the adjacent numeral ''hat'' '6'.}} M \u0441\u0430\u0442 /sat/, Kh \u0442\u0430\u043f\u04d9\u0442 /tap\u0259t/ (from an [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] source; cf. [[Sanskrit]] ''sapt\u00e1'', [[Avestan]] ''hapta'', both from [[Proto-Indo-Iranian language|Proto-Indo-Iranian]] ''*sapt\u00e1'' < [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] ''{{PIE|*sept\u1e3f\u0325}}'').\n\n''Names'' of two of the Ugric peoples are cognate as well: Hungarian ''magyar'' 'Hungarian' can be equated with ''Mansi'' (from an original root *m\u00e4\u0144\u0107-). A related word in Khanty denotes a specific [[phratry]].\n\nA common derivational innovation is seen in the word for 'louse': Proto-Uralic *t\u00e4ji \u2192 *t\u00e4(j)-ktVmV \u2192 H ''tet\u0171'', M \u0442\u0430\u043a\u044d\u043c, Kh \u0442\u0435\u0432\u0442\u04d9\u043c.\n\n==Structural features==\n* An original [[ablative]] case marked by ''-l''\n* A series of original [[locative]] cases, formed from postpositions derived from a pronoun root ''*n\u00e4''\n* [[Possessive suffix]]es are placed before [[case suffix]]es, not after them as in the other Uralic languages\n* A class of \"instable\" verb stems, in which alternation between CV and CVC stem variants occurs, e.g. ''to take': Hungarian ''v\u00eb-'' ~ ''v\u00ebv-'' ~ ''[[wiktionary:vesz|v\u00ebsz-]]'', Mansi *wi- ~ *w\u00e6j-, Khanty *w\u0115- ~ *w\u0115j-.\n* Distinct attributive and nominal forms of the numeral '2': Hungarian ''[[wiktionary:k\u00e9t|k\u00e9t]]'' vs. ''[[wiktionary:kett\u0151|kett\u0151]]'', Mansi \u043a\u0438\u0442 vs. \u043a\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0433, Khanty (Northern) \u043a\u0430\u0442 vs. \u043a\u0430\u0442\u04d9\u043d, (Eastern) {{IPA|/k\u00e6t/}} vs. {{IPA|/k\u00e6t\u0259\u0263/}}\n* Found in Hungarian and Mansi, an extended form of the [[caritive]] suffix containing ''-l''.\n* Distinct verb conjugations according to the [[transitivity (grammatical category)|transitivity]] of the verb. It is sometimes termed as \u201cdefinite\u201d versus \u201cindefinite\u201d conjugation, because also the [[definiteness]] of the [[Object (grammar)|object]] can play a role when selecting between the two. This feature is within the Uralic family also found in the [[Mordvinic languages]], and it is likely to not represent a common Ugric innovation; the particular details of the construction are different in all three Ugric languages.\n* Verbal prefixes, which modify the meaning of the verb in both concrete and abstract ways\n\n;Examples from Mansi\n\n\u0113l(a) \u2013 'forwards, onwards, away'\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| j\u014dm- 'to go, to stride' || \u0113l-j\u014dm- 'to go away/on'\n|-\n| tinal- 'to sell' || \u0113l-tinal- 'to sell off'\n|}\n\nxot \u2013 'direction away from something and other nuances of action intensity'\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| min- 'to go' || xot-min- 'to go away, to stop'\n|-\n| roxt- 'to be frightened' || xot-roxt- 'to take fright suddenly'\n|}\n\n;Examples from Hungarian\n\nel \u2013 'away, off'\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| ugrik 'to jump' || elugrik 'to jump away'\n|-\n| mosolyog 'to smile' || elmosolyodik 'to start to smile' (implying a lack of control)\n|}\n\nki \u2013 'out (of)'\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| ugrik 'to jump' || kiugrik 'to jump out'\n|-\n| n\u00e9z 'to look' || kin\u00e9z 'to look out'\n|}\n\nIn Hungarian, the [[citation form]] of verbs is the present tense of the 3rd person singular form, which is given here, which does not have any suffixes.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Uralic languages]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|1}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n*{{cite journal|last=Honti|first=L\u00e1szl\u00f3|title=Features of Ugric Languages (Observations on the Question of Ugric Unity)|year=1979|pages=1\u201325|volume=29|journal=Acta Linguistica Academia Scientiarum Hungaricae}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Honti|first=L\u00e1szl\u00f3|title=Ugrilainen kantakieli \u2013 erheellinen vai reaalinen hypoteesi?|year=1998|volume=228|journal=Suomalais-Ugrilaisen Seuran toimituksia|isbn=952-5150-15-1}}\n*{{cite book |last=Riese |first=Timothy |title=Vogul: Languages of the World/Materials 158 |url=http://www.lincom.at |publisher=Lincom Europa |year=2001 |isbn=3-89586-231-2}}\n*{{cite book |last=T\u00f6rkenczy |first=Mikl\u00f3s |title=Hungarian Verbs & Essentials of Grammar |publisher=Passport Books |year=1997 |isbn=0-8442-8350-9}}\n\n{{Uralic languages}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Uralic languages]]\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ugric_languages"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic on Charles de Gaulle", "text_new": "{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on Charles de Gaulle}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:2020 coronavirus pandemic on ''Charles de Gaulle''}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic on board ''Charles de Gaulle''\n| image = French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle (R91) underway on 24 April 2019 (190424-M-BP588-1005).jpg\n| caption = ''Charles de Gaulle'' in April 2019\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[North Sea]]\n| first_case = {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}}\n| arrival_date = 10 April 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=04|day1=10|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 1,081<ref >{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/covid-19-940-marins-positifs-sur-le-charles-de-gaulle-et-son-escorte-20200417|title=Covid-19: 1081 marins positifs sur le \"Charles de Gaulle\" et son escorte|trans-title=Covid-19: 1081 positive sailors on the \"Charles de Gaulle\" and his escort|website=lefigaro.fr|date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the French aircraft carrier {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}} on 10 April 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\nThe {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}} had left [[Brest, France|Brest]] on 15 March 2020 after a two-day stop and the crew did not have contact with the outside world until mid-April 2020.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/16/inquiry-french-aircraft-carrier-crew-catch-coronavirus-charles-de-gaulle  Kim Willsher and Dan Sabbagh: \"Inquiry after 668 of French aircraft carrier's crew catch coronavirus \"] [[The Guardian]] 16 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"franceinfo\"/>\n\nThe ship was on a months-long mission leading a [[carrier battle group#France|carrier battle group]] when its first coronavirus case was reported.<ref name=\"leopold.naval\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.navalnews.com/naval-news/2020/01/french-carrier-strike-group-begins-foch-deployment/|title=French Carrier Strike Group Begins 'Foch' Deployment|date=22 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"leopold.bruxelles2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bruxelles2.eu/2020/04/covid-19-did-belgium-make-the-right-choice-by-interrupting-the-foch-mission/?lang=en|title=Covid-19. Did Belgium make the right choice by interrupting the Foch mission|first=Nicolas|last=Gros-Verheyde|date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Another ship participating in the mission, Belgium's {{ship|Belgian frigate|Leopold I|F930|2}}, broke off to return to port weeks earlier due to a case of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on military ships#Leopold I|coronavirus being found on board]].<ref name=\"leopold.bruxelles2\" />\n\nThere were a couple of minor colds among the crew, but it did not raise alarms because there was a strong wind and temperatures of -5\u00b0C. <ref name=\"figaro\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/france-un-tiers-des-marins-du-porte-avions-charles-de-gaulle-positifs-au-coronavirus-20200415|title=Coronavirus: un tiers des marins du porte-avions Charles-de-Gaulle sont infect\u00e9s|language=fr|access-date=18 April 2020|website=[[Le Figaro]]}}</ref> It was not until about 40 crew members were beginning to show symptoms, that the carrier set sail to its home port in [[Toulon]] earlier than planned, as reported on 8 April 2020 by the [[Ministry of Armed Forces (France)|Ministry of Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/fr/20200408-coronavirus-plusieurs-cas-suspects-\u00e0-bord-du-porte-avions-fran\u00e7ais-charles-de-gaulle |title=Coronavirus : plusieurs cas suspects \u00e0 bord du porte-avions fran\u00e7ais Charles-de-Gaulle |language=French |work=France 24 |trans-title=Coronavirus: several suspected cases on board the French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters-heading\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-france-military/french-military-ship-heading-back-to-port-due-to-possible-covid-19-cases-idUSKBN21Q0SY |title=French aircraft carrier heads home early due to possible COVID-19 cases |work=Reuters |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> After 66 tests were conducted on board, the ministry announced on 10 April that 50 tests had returned positive.<ref name=\"gaulle.parisien\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/coronavirus-50-cas-de-contamination-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-trois-marins-evacues-10-04-2020-8297511.php |title=Coronavirus : 50 cas de contamination \u00e0 bord du \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", trois marins \u00e9vacu\u00e9s |work=Le Parisien |language=French |date=10 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Three sailors were evacuated by air to {{ill|Saint Anne Army Teaching Hospital|fr|H\u00f4pital d'instruction des arm\u00e9es Sainte-Anne}}.<ref name=\"gaulle.parisien\" /><ref name=\"gaulle.times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/10/world/europe/10reuters-health-coronavirus-france-aircraftcarrier.html|title=France Reports 50 COVID-19 Cases Aboard Aircraft Carrier |website=The New York Times |agency=Reuters |date=10 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> There are 1,760 personnel on board.<ref name=\"reuters-heading\"/> \nThe carrier arrived in Toulon on the afternoon of 12 April where the personnel is quarantined for 14 days.<ref name=\"franceinfo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-le-porte-avions-francais-charles-de-gaulle-et-ses-50-cas-de-covid-19-a-bord-est-attendu-a-toulon-dimanche-apres-midi_3910907.html|title=Coronavirus : le porte-avions fran\u00e7ais \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", et ses 50 cas de Covid-19 \u00e0 bord, est attendu \u00e0 Toulon dimanche apr\u00e8s-midi|language=fr|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"europe1_between\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.europe1.fr/societe/covid-19-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-les-marins-qui-nont-pas-respecte-les-regles-doivent-etre-sanctionnes-3961696|title=Les marins du Charles-de-Gaulle \"qui n\u2019ont pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles doivent \u00eatre sanctionn\u00e9s\" |access-date=18 April 2020|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nAt first, the origin of the outbreak was unknown; there had been no contact with the outside world after the ship made a stopover in [[Brest, France|Brest]] the middle of March.<ref name=\"franceinfo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-le-porte-avions-francais-charles-de-gaulle-et-ses-50-cas-de-covid-19-a-bord-est-attendu-a-toulon-dimanche-apres-midi_3910907.html|title=Coronavirus : le porte-avions fran\u00e7ais \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", et ses 50 cas de Covid-19 \u00e0 bord, est attendu \u00e0 Toulon dimanche apr\u00e8s-midi|language=fr|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"europe1_between\"/>{{efn|between 13 en 16 March}} The captain had given the crew orders to avoid an infection; a family day was cancelled. \nThe girlfriend of a sailor said in an interview on [[Easter Sunday]] that some sailors had eaten in the same restaurants as their wives or families. She also said that sailors of other nationalities had been there, too.<ref>http://www.europe1.fr: [https://www.europe1.fr/societe/covid-19-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-les-marins-qui-nont-pas-respecte-les-regles-doivent-etre-sanctionnes-3961696 ''Les marins du Charles-de-Gaulle \"qui n\u2019ont pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles doivent \u00eatre sanctionn\u00e9s\"]</ref> As of 18 April, Brest is considered the point of infection. <ref name=\"franceinfo-04-18\"/>\n\nOn 15 April 2020, the Ministry of Armed Forces reported that, out of the 1767 tests conducted on the members of the carrier battle group, 668 returned positive, with the vast majority of cases being aboard ''Charles de Gaulle''.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\">https://mobile.twitter.com/Armees_Gouv/status/1250513114161909763</ref>{{efn|30% of the tests were still inconclusive.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" />}}  The 1700 sailors of ''Charles de Gaulle'' were subsequently quarantined for two weeks.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" /><ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" /><ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.bleu\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/societe/coronavirus-au-moins-500-marins-du-charles-de-gaulle-positifs-au-covid-19-1586960222 |title = Coronavirus : Pr\u00e8s de 700 marins positifs au Covid-19, la majorit\u00e9 sur le porte-avions Charles de Gaulle|date = 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, the numbers reported went up to more than 1000 infected, from 2000 tested, with 500 showing symptoms, 24 admitted to hospital and one of them to an [[intensive care unit]] (ICU).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/corona-frankreich-flugzeugtraeger-101.html |title = 1000 Seeleute auf \"Charles de Gaulle\" infiziert}}</ref> Press reported that not all tests haven been finished, so actual numbers could be even higher at this point.\n\n[[File:US_Navy_110321-N-0000X-027_Adm._Samuel_J._Locklear,_III_speaks_with_an_aircrew_team_from_the_French_Navy_aircraft_carrier_Charles_de_Gaulle_(R91).jpg|thumb|Admiral [[Samuel J. Locklear]] inside ''Charles de Gaulle'' (2011)]]\nOn 18 April, it was reported that 1,081 out of 2,300 people on both ''Charles de Gaulle'' and its escort, [[frigate]] {{ship|French frigate|Chevalier Paul||2}}, tested positive. Two investigations have been launched. One on the situation in Brest and one lead by admiral [[Christophe Prazuck]] on the epidemic on board of the carrier strike group.<ref name=\"figaro\"/> According to Admiral Alain Coldefy there were places on the carrier where 20 people slept together on three or four floors of [[Berth (sleeping)|berths]]. <ref name=\"franceinfo-04-18\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/marins-contamines-au-covid-19-sur-le-charles-de-gaulle-a-des-endroits-il-y-a-une-vingtaine-de-matelots-qui-dorment-sur-3-ou-4-etages-de-couchettes_3922411.html |title=Marins contamin\u00e9s au Covid-19 sur le \"Charles-de-Gaulle\" : \"\u00c0 des endroits, il y a une vingtaine de matelots qui dorment sur 3 ou 4 \u00e9tages de couchettes\" |language=fr |access-date=18 April 2020| website=franceinfo}}</ref>\n\n==Number of confirmed cases==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width= <!-- 300 -->\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 10 Apr, 15 Apr, 18 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y1= 50, 668, 1081\n|y1Title=Confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{#related:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in military history]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by location|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:History of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in Europe]]\n[[Category:Military history of the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Water transport in the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in Europe]]\n[[Category:Disasters in the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Health and transport]]\n[[Category:Health and military]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on Charles de Gaulle}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:2020 coronavirus pandemic on ''Charles de Gaulle''}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic on board ''Charles de Gaulle''\n| image = French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle (R91) underway on 24 April 2019 (190424-M-BP588-1005).jpg\n| caption = ''Charles de Gaulle'' in April 2019\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[North Sea]]\n| first_case = {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}}\n| arrival_date = 10 April 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=04|day1=10|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 1,081<ref >{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/covid-19-940-marins-positifs-sur-le-charles-de-gaulle-et-son-escorte-20200417|title=Covid-19: 1081 marins positifs sur le \"Charles de Gaulle\" et son escorte|trans-title=Covid-19: 1081 positive sailors on the \"Charles de Gaulle\" and his escort|website=lefigaro.fr|date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the French aircraft carrier {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}} on 10 April 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\nThe {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}} had left [[Brest, France|Brest]] on 15 March 2020 after a two day stop and the crew did not have contact with the outside world until mid-April 2020.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/16/inquiry-french-aircraft-carrier-crew-catch-coronavirus-charles-de-gaulle  Kim Willsher and Dan Sabbagh: \"Inquiry after 668 of French aircraft carrier's crew catch coronavirus \"] [[The Guardian]] 16 April 2020</ref><ref name=\"franceinfo\"/>\n\nThe ship was on a months-long mission leading a [[carrier battle group#France|carrier battle group]] when its first coronavirus case was reported.<ref name=\"leopold.naval\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.navalnews.com/naval-news/2020/01/french-carrier-strike-group-begins-foch-deployment/|title=French Carrier Strike Group Begins 'Foch' Deployment|date=22 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"leopold.bruxelles2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bruxelles2.eu/2020/04/covid-19-did-belgium-make-the-right-choice-by-interrupting-the-foch-mission/?lang=en|title=Covid-19. Did Belgium make the right choice by interrupting the Foch mission|first=Nicolas|last=Gros-Verheyde|date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Another ship participating in the mission, Belgium's {{ship|Belgian frigate|Leopold I|F930|2}}, broke off to return to port weeks earlier due to a case of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on military ships#Leopold I|coronavirus being found on board]].<ref name=\"leopold.bruxelles2\" />\n\nThere were a couple of minor colds among the crew, but it did not raise alarms because there was a strong wind and temperatures of -5\u00b0C. <ref name=\"figaro\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/france-un-tiers-des-marins-du-porte-avions-charles-de-gaulle-positifs-au-coronavirus-20200415|title=Coronavirus: un tiers des marins du porte-avions Charles-de-Gaulle sont infect\u00e9s|language=fr|access-date=18 April 2020|website=[[Le Figaro]]}}</ref> It was not until about 40 crew members were beginning to show symptoms, that the carrier set sail to its home port in [[Toulon]] earlier than planned, as reported on 8 April 2020 by the [[Ministry of Armed Forces (France)|Ministry of Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/fr/20200408-coronavirus-plusieurs-cas-suspects-\u00e0-bord-du-porte-avions-fran\u00e7ais-charles-de-gaulle |title=Coronavirus : plusieurs cas suspects \u00e0 bord du porte-avions fran\u00e7ais Charles-de-Gaulle |language=French |work=France 24 |trans-title=Coronavirus: several suspected cases on board the French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters-heading\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-france-military/french-military-ship-heading-back-to-port-due-to-possible-covid-19-cases-idUSKBN21Q0SY |title=French aircraft carrier heads home early due to possible COVID-19 cases |work=Reuters |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> After 66 tests were conducted on board, the ministry announced on 10 April that 50 tests had returned positive.<ref name=\"gaulle.parisien\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/coronavirus-50-cas-de-contamination-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-trois-marins-evacues-10-04-2020-8297511.php |title=Coronavirus : 50 cas de contamination \u00e0 bord du \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", trois marins \u00e9vacu\u00e9s |work=Le Parisien |language=French |date=10 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Three sailors were evacuated by air to {{ill|Saint Anne Army Teaching Hospital|fr|H\u00f4pital d'instruction des arm\u00e9es Sainte-Anne}}.<ref name=\"gaulle.parisien\" /><ref name=\"gaulle.times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/10/world/europe/10reuters-health-coronavirus-france-aircraftcarrier.html|title=France Reports 50 COVID-19 Cases Aboard Aircraft Carrier |website=The New York Times |agency=Reuters |date=10 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> There are 1,760 personnel on board.<ref name=\"reuters-heading\"/> \nThe carrier arrived in Toulon on the afternoon of 12 April where the personnel is quarantined for 14 days.<ref name=\"franceinfo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-le-porte-avions-francais-charles-de-gaulle-et-ses-50-cas-de-covid-19-a-bord-est-attendu-a-toulon-dimanche-apres-midi_3910907.html|title=Coronavirus : le porte-avions fran\u00e7ais \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", et ses 50 cas de Covid-19 \u00e0 bord, est attendu \u00e0 Toulon dimanche apr\u00e8s-midi|language=fr|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"europe1_between\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.europe1.fr/societe/covid-19-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-les-marins-qui-nont-pas-respecte-les-regles-doivent-etre-sanctionnes-3961696|title=Les marins du Charles-de-Gaulle \"qui n\u2019ont pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles doivent \u00eatre sanctionn\u00e9s\" |access-date=18 April 2020|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nAt first, the origin of the outbreak was unknown; there had been no contact with the outside world after the ship made a stopover in [[Brest, France|Brest]] the middle of March.<ref name=\"franceinfo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-le-porte-avions-francais-charles-de-gaulle-et-ses-50-cas-de-covid-19-a-bord-est-attendu-a-toulon-dimanche-apres-midi_3910907.html|title=Coronavirus : le porte-avions fran\u00e7ais \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", et ses 50 cas de Covid-19 \u00e0 bord, est attendu \u00e0 Toulon dimanche apr\u00e8s-midi|language=fr|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"europe1_between\"/>{{efn|between 13 en 16 March}} The captain had given the crew orders to avoid an infection; a family day was cancelled. \nThe girlfriend of a sailor said in an interview on [[Easter Sunday]] that some sailors had eaten in the same restaurants as their wives or families. She also said that sailors of other nationalities had been there, too.<ref>http://www.europe1.fr: [https://www.europe1.fr/societe/covid-19-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-les-marins-qui-nont-pas-respecte-les-regles-doivent-etre-sanctionnes-3961696 ''Les marins du Charles-de-Gaulle \"qui n\u2019ont pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles doivent \u00eatre sanctionn\u00e9s\"]</ref> As of 18 April, Brest is considered the point of infection. <ref name=\"franceinfo-04-18\"/>\n\nOn 15 April 2020, the Ministry of Armed Forces reported that, out of the 1767 tests conducted on the members of the carrier battle group, 668 returned positive, with the vast majority of cases being aboard ''Charles de Gaulle''.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\">https://mobile.twitter.com/Armees_Gouv/status/1250513114161909763</ref>{{efn|30% of the tests were still inconclusive.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" />}}  The 1700 sailors of ''Charles de Gaulle'' were subsequently quarantined for two weeks.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" /><ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" /><ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.bleu\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/societe/coronavirus-au-moins-500-marins-du-charles-de-gaulle-positifs-au-covid-19-1586960222 |title = Coronavirus : Pr\u00e8s de 700 marins positifs au Covid-19, la majorit\u00e9 sur le porte-avions Charles de Gaulle|date = 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, the numbers reported went up to more than 1000 infected, from 2000 tested, with 500 showing symptoms, 24 admitted to hospital and one of them to an [[intensive care unit]] (ICU).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/corona-frankreich-flugzeugtraeger-101.html |title = 1000 Seeleute auf \"Charles de Gaulle\" infiziert}}</ref> Press reported that not all tests haven been finished, so actual numbers could be even higher at this point.\n\n[[File:US_Navy_110321-N-0000X-027_Adm._Samuel_J._Locklear,_III_speaks_with_an_aircrew_team_from_the_French_Navy_aircraft_carrier_Charles_de_Gaulle_(R91).jpg|thumb|Admiral [[Samuel J. Locklear]] inside ''Charles de Gaulle'' (2011)]]\nOn 18 April, it was reported that 1,081 out of 2,300 people on both ''Charles de Gaulle'' and its escort, [[frigate]] {{ship|French frigate|Chevalier Paul||2}}, tested positive. Two investigations have been launched. One on the situation in Brest and one lead by admiral [[Christophe Prazuck]] on the epidemic on board of the carrier strike group.<ref name=\"figaro\"/> According to Admiral Alain Coldefy there were places on the carrier where 20 people slept together on three or four floors of [[Berth (sleeping)|berths]]. <ref 