_year      = 1986\n| draft_round     = 2\n| draft_pick      = 28\n| draft_team      = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| career_start    = 1986\n| career_end      = 1998\n| career_number = 42\n| career_position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| coach_start     = 1998\n| coach_end       = \n| years1          = {{nbay|1986|full=y}}\n| team1           = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| years2          = {{nbay|1987|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1991|end}}\n| team2           = [[Milwaukee Bucks]]\n| years3          = {{nbay|1992|full=y}}\n| team3           = [[Utah Jazz]]\n| years4          = {{nbay|1993|full=y}}\n| team4           = [[Orlando Magic]]\n| years5          = {{nbay|1994|full=y}}\n| team5           = [[Chicago Bulls]]\n| years6          = 1995\u20131996\n| team6           = [[Levallois Sporting Club|Levallois]]\n| years7          = {{nbay|1996|end}}\n| team7           = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| years8          = 1997\u20131998\n| team8           = [[Idaho Stampede]]\n| cyears1         = 1998\u20132000\n| cteam1          = [[Montana Grizzlies men's basketball|Montana]] (assistant)\n| cyears2         = 2001\u20132002\n| cteam2          = [[Old Dominion Monarchs basketball|Old Dominion]] (assistant)\n| cyears3         = 2003\u20132004\n| cteam3          = Idaho Stampede\n| cyears4         = 2004\u20132006\n| cteam4          = Montana\n| cyears5         = {{nbay|2006|full=yes}}\n| cteam5          = Milwaukee Bucks (assistant)\n| cyears6         = {{nbay|2006|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2007|end}}\n| cteam6          = Milwaukee Bucks\n| cyears7         = 2010\n| cteam7          = [[United States men's national basketball team|USA U18 men's national team]]\n| cyears8         = {{nbay|2010|full=yes}}\n| cteam8          = [[New Jersey Nets]] (assistant)\n| cyears9         = 2011\u2013present\n| cteam9          = [[Utah Utes men's basketball|Utah]]\n| highlights      = \n'''As player:'''\n* 3\u00d7 [[Big Sky Conference Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Big Sky Player of the Year]] (1984\u20131986)\n'''As coach:'''\n* 2\u00d7 [[Big Sky Men's Basketball Tournament|Big Sky Tournament]] champion (2004, [[2005 Big Sky Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|2005]])\n* Pac-12 AP Coach of the Year ([[2017\u201318 Pac-12 Conference men's basketball season|2018]])\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label      = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value      = 3,425 (8.2 ppg)\n| stat2label      = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value      = 2,051 (4.9 rpg)\n| stat3label      = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value      = 513 (1.2 apg)\n| bbr             = krystla01\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's basketball}}\n{{MedalCountry|USA}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Under-19 World Championship|FIBA U19 World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[FIBA Under-19 World Championship|1983 Palma de Mallorca]] | [[United States national basketball team|National team]]}}\n}}\n'''Larry Brett Krystkowiak''' ({{IPAc-en|k|r|\u1d7b|s|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|v|i|\u00e6|k}} {{respell|kris|KOH|vee-ak}};<ref>http://www.nba.com/global/intl_player_pronunciation_070426.html</ref> born September 23, 1964) is a retired American professional basketball player, and current head coach of the [[Utah Utes men's basketball]] team.<ref name=\"utahUtes\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.utahutes.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/m-baskbl-coaching-staff.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=April 3, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401021339/http://www.utahutes.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/m-baskbl-coaching-staff.html |archive-date=April 1, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"dbBasketball\">[https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/k/krystla01.html BasketballReference entry]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in [[Missoula, Montana]]<ref name=\"dbBasketball\"/> to Bernard and Helen Krystkowiak.<ref name=\"sltrib\">[http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/utes/51767144-89/larry-krystkowiak-coach-montana.html.csp sltrib.com]</ref>  At a young age, his mother always encouraged Larry to participate in sports.<ref name=\"si1985\">[https://www.si.com/vault/1985/02/04/627679/he-has-taken-some-tough-shots si.com He Has Taken Some Tough Shots]</ref>  His mother died of [[Hodgkin's lymphoma]] when he was eight years old<ref name=\"grfx\">[http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/utah/sports/m-baskbl/auto_pdf/2011-12/misc_non_event/CoachKBasketballTimes.pdf Basketball Times.  Vol. 34. No.1.  Sept 2011.]</ref> and his father remarried.  He primarily grew up in [[Shelby, Montana]], and his step-mother did not approve of Larry playing sports.<ref name=\"sltrib\"/>  At the age of 15, Larry moved out of Shelby and finished his high school career at [[Big Sky High School]] in [[Missoula, Montana|Missoula]].<ref name=krystkowiak2>{{cite web|title=125 Montana Newsmakers: Larry Krystkowiak|url=http://www.greatfallstribune.com/multimedia/125newsmakers5/krystkowiak.html|work=Great Falls Tribune|author=Tribune Staff|accessdate=August 24, 2011}}</ref> During this time he lived with his older brother Bernie,<ref name=\"sltrib\"/> who became Larry's legal guardian.<ref name=\"si1985\"/>\n\n==College career==\nKrystkowiak played college basketball for the [[University of Montana \u2013 Missoula|University of Montana]] from 1982 to 1986 and still holds the school records for career points scored (2,017) and  rebounds (1,105).<ref name=\"NBABio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/coachfile/larry_krystkowiak/index.html |title=NBA.com bio |access-date=March 15, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070318061332/http://www.nba.com/coachfile/larry_krystkowiak/index.html |archive-date=March 18, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  He is the only person to have been named [[Big Sky Conference]] MVP three times (1984\u20131986).<ref name=\"KryskoHiredAtUM\">[http://missoulian.com/articles/2007/01/15/grizmania/news/egriz83.txt Missoulian.com]</ref>\n\n==Professional playing career==\nKrystkowiak was selected by the [[Chicago Bulls]] in the 2nd round (28th overall pick) of the [[1986 NBA draft]]. He played power forward for nine seasons in the NBA, spending the bulk of his career with the [[Milwaukee Bucks]].  He also played for the [[San Antonio Spurs]], [[Utah Jazz]], [[Orlando Magic]], [[Chicago Bulls]] and [[Los Angeles Lakers]]. In the 1988\u201389 season he averaged 12.7 points, 7.6 rebounds, 1.3 assists and over 30 minutes per game for the Bucks.<ref name=\"dbBasketball\"/> Over his NBA career, he averaged 8.1 points and 4.9 rebounds per contest.<ref name=\"dbBasketball\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Early career===\nKrystkowiak began his coaching career in 1998 as an assistant to Don Holst at his alma mater, the [[University of Montana \u2013 Missoula|University of Montana]].  He coached at Montana until 2000 when he left to join [[Old Dominion Monarchs basketball|Old Dominion]] as an assistant under former Griz head coach, [[Blaine Taylor]].<ref name=\"KryskoHiredAtUM\" /> He spent one season (2001\u20132002) at Old Dominion.\n\nKrystkowiak got his first opportunity as a head coach with the [[Continental Basketball Association|CBA's]] [[Idaho Stampede]] in 2003\u201304.  In his single season as the Stampede's head coach, he led the team to a 37\u201316 record and a CBA championship game berth.<ref name=\"NBABio\"/>\n\nHe was hired as head men's basketball coach at the [[University of Montana \u2013 Missoula|University of Montana]] in May 2004.  He led the Griz to a 42\u201320 overall record over the course of the next two seasons, reaching the NCAA tournament each year as a result of winning the [[Big Sky Conference]] tourney.  In 2006 the Grizzlies beat heavily favored, fifth seed, [[University of Nevada, Reno|Nevada]], in the [[2006 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]].\n\n===NBA coaching career===\n\nIn June 2006 Krystkowiak left Montana to take a job as an assistant coach with the Milwaukee Bucks under [[Terry Stotts]].  Krystkowiak was responsible for working with the Milwaukee's big men, notably second year players [[Andrew Bogut]] and [[Charlie Villanueva]].<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=439859 Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929133549/http://www.jsonline.com/story/index.aspx?id=439859 |date=September 29, 2007 }}</ref> He was named head coach of the team on March 14, 2007, after Stotts was fired.  Stotts had led the Bucks to a 23\u201341 record during the 2006\u201307 season.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/bucks/news/Krystkowiak_340_255_070314.html NBA.com Krystkowiak replaces Stotts]</ref>  He signed a reported 4-year contract with the Bucks, with an average annual salary of $2&nbsp;million<ref>[http://www.jsonline.com/watch/?watch=1&date=March 15, 2007&id=20650 info on Krytkowiak/Bucks contract] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022185905/http://www.jsonline.com/watch/?watch=1 |date=October 22, 2008 }}</ref> Krystkowiak's NBA head coaching debut on March 15, 2007, resulted in a 101\u201390 victory over the San Antonio Spurs.\n\nOn April 17, 2008, Krystkowiak was fired as Milwaukee Bucks head coach after a disappointing season in which the Bucks compiled the league's sixth worst record.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3351403 ESPN.com story on Bucks firing]</ref>\n\nIn July 2010 Krystkowiak joined the [[New Jersey Nets]] coaching staff alongside [[Avery Johnson]] and [[Sam Mitchell (basketball)|Sam Mitchell]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/new-york/nba/news/story?id=5391938 Mitchell, Krystkowiak join Nets staff]</ref>\n\n===University of Utah===\n\nOn April 3, 2011, it was announced that Krystkowiak would take over the head coaching position for the University of Utah men's basketball team, as they transitioned into Utah's first season in the newly realigned Pac-12.<ref name=\"sltrib\"/>\n\nAfter Krystkowiak was named Utah's head coach, eight (8) players left the program to play elsewhere and he was forced to bring in several junior college and walk-on players to fill his depleted roster.  In a season where starting center David Foster missed the entire season and starting point guard Josh \"Jiggy\" Watkins was dismissed halfway through,  Krystkowiak and the Utes struggled to a 6-25 finish, including only three wins against their new Pac-12 opponents.\n\nThe [[2012\u201313 Utah Utes men's basketball team|2012\u20132013]] season showed much improvement for Krystkowiak's Utes.  The additions of freshmen Jordan Loveridge and Brandon Taylor, as well as great play and leadership from senior center Jason Washburn, would help Utah more than double their win total from the previous season.  On March 9, 2013, Utah closed out its season by defeating No. 19 Oregon, celebrating Senior Night at the Huntsman Center with the program's first victory over a ranked opponent since 2009. Utah then defeated USC and California in the first and second rounds of the Pac-12 tournament before losing a rematch with Oregon, the eventual champion.\n\nKrystkowiak's third season saw the [[2013\u201314 Utah Utes men's basketball team|2013\u20132014 Runnin' Utes]] reach their first postseason tournament under the coach.  The addition of transfer point guard Delon Wright and an improved core of players led Utah to a 21-12 record, receiving an at-large bid to the [[2014 NIT|NIT]]. The next year, he led his team to the sweet sixteen, their highest run in the tournament in years. In 2017\u201318, he led the Utes to their first NIT finals appearance in 44 years. \n\nThe [[National Polish-American Sports Hall of Fame]] nominated Krystkowiak for its Class of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Election results |url=http://polishsportshof.com/organization/election-results/ |publisher=National Polish-American Sports Hall of Fame |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130621233915/http://polishsportshof.com/organization/election-results/ |archivedate=June 21, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On June 21, 2018 Krystkowiak will be enshrined into the  [[National Polish-American Sports Hall of Fame]] as a member of the Class of 2018 in Troy, Michigan.\n\n==Personal life==\nLarry and his wife, Jan, have five children, Cam, Luc, Ben and twin girls Samantha and Finley.<ref name=\"NBABio\"/> He has seen his father only once in over 30 years, because of the issues in his early life.<ref name=\"grfx\"/>\n\n==Head coaching record==\nLarry Krystkowiak's record as a head coach.\n\n=== CBA ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! colspan=\"5\"|Regular Season !! colspan=\"1\"|Post Season\n|-\n! G !! W !! L !! Pct!!Finish !! Result\n|- \n! [[Idaho Stampede]] ||2003\u201304<ref name=\"NBABio\"/>\n|53||37||16||.698|||| Lost CBA championship game\n|}\n\n===College===\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = | conference = | postseason= | poll = }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name       = [[Montana Grizzlies basketball|Montana Grizzlies]]\n | conference = [[Big Sky Conference]]\n | startyear  = 2004\n | endyear    = 2006\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = conference tournament \n | season       = [[2004\u201305 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2004\u201305]]\n | name         = Montana\n | overall      = 18\u201313\n | conference   = 9\u20135\n | confstanding = 2nd\n | postseason   = [[2005 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA First Round]]\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = conference tournament\n | season       = [[2005\u201306 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2005\u201306]]\n | name         = Montana\n | overall      = 24\u20137\n | conference   = 10\u20134\n | confstanding = 2nd\n | postseason   = [[2006 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Second Round]]\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Montana\n | overall    = 42\u201320 ({{Winning percentage|42|20}})\n | confrecord = 19\u20139 ({{Winning percentage|19|